e Philippines among the world\u2019s middle-range users. However, the rural population, which comprises about 90 percent of the total population, has very limited access to electricity. Rural electrification", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ead07269-3233-4dd3-bea0-380bede69ade": {"__data__": {"id_": "ead07269-3233-4dd3-bea0-380bede69ade", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in the Philippines", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6033c24a601ca624819ba788d7524e7d55a048660da1c871116016a09c5129f1"}, "3": {"node_id": "fa7a6813-c667-4530-a8c6-75ebaa0fb2e0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c4074aaf5972382cd5284aa175f9b55e7cddc263b97b7e87e4744bdbd4af27e8"}}, "hash": "2c493ccf773fd7a9cefb5e92a41217614f243251e1c4559511f50732d7da9d34", "text": "rates vary widely from province to province. The statistics on household connections and energization of power lines further vary at the level of barangays. According to electrification data of the National Electrification Administration (NEA), while there is complete BACKGROUND 3 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES electrification at the municipal level and 92 percent electrification at the barangay level, the national average of electrified households is only 62 percent. For provinces with low electrification rates (between 13 and 30 percent), improvements in the growth rate of electrification may not take place in the next decade. This could be because of the currently unviable nature of grid extensions carried out by electric cooperatives in these areas. This is particularly true in the island provinces. Other options need to be tried to accomplish the goal of total electrification at the barangay level. The important role of renewable energy (RE) has been recognized, as the country increases its RE capacities in grid and off-grid locations through the use of solar, hydro, biomass, wind and geothermal resources. The Department of Energy (DoE) targets to double its RE-based capacity in the next 10 years, as mentioned in the RE Policy Framework for on- and off-grid areas. The plans include 130 to 250 MW of capacity from solar, biomass and ocean; 2,950 MW of hydropower; 1,200 MW of capacity from geothermal power plants; and 417 MW of wind power generation. In this analysis, it is noteworthy that there is a strong correlation between the levels of electrification and poverty. The challenge for the Philippines to reduce poverty and enhance gender equity can be met by providing access to energy services to about one-third of its population. An assessment of the energy sector puts forth a number of challenges to be met in terms of linking energy and poverty concerns, and providing affordable energy access to the poor. For example, agencies such as the National Power Corporation\u2013Small Power Utilities Group (NPC\u2013SPUG) have found in surveys that electricity is not among the top critical needs of the poor population. Some of these challenges are identified and discussed below. THE CHALLENGES Absence of a designated central body and coordinating mechanism to link energy with poverty T he existing institutional framework for the energy sector is limited primarily to DoE and its affiliates for various functions. Under DoE are the Energy Utilization Management Bureau, the Energy Industry Administration Bureau and the Energy Policy and Planning Bureau. The energy-related programmes of these institutions have concentrated on viable areas with established systems to satisfy financial covenants. Therefore, a new institutional framework and mechanism has been installed under the Expanded Rural Electrification Programme to handle the remaining unviable areas. Table 1 summarizes the institutional framework of rural electrification. There is a strong correlation between the levels of electrification and poverty. 4 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES TABLE 1 INSTITUTIONAL ARRANGEMENTS IN RURAL/ MISSIONARY ELECTRIFICATION Institution Department of Energy (DoE) Energy Regulatory Commission (ERC) National Electrification Administration (NEA) National Power Corporation\u2013 Small Power Utilities Group (NPC/SPUG) Distribution utilities and electric cooperatives Other government agencies, such as the Department of Agrarian Reforms and the Department of Interior and Local Government Role Policy direction, goal setting, programme management and coordination Rate design, licensing and determination of universal charge, and approval from the Missionary Electrification Development Plan in coordination with DoE Administration of electric cooperatives, and project identification and monitoring of missionary electrification projects Project implementation and petitioning for the universal charge for missionary electrification Project implementation and operation Financing support and project implementation While individual agencies carry out some activities that link energy service delivery to poverty reduction, a central coordinating mechanism with unified performance indicators to link these issues is absent. With the Government\u2019s thrust on decentralization, community-level services \u2013 including energy provision \u2013 have been started. Certain local initiatives, using meagre resources, too have been started. Electric cooperatives are unable to extend services to about 38 percent of the households. In most cases, the activities of RE-oriented non-governmental organizations (NGOs) are not coordinated with electric cooperatives that work through franchisees. At the community level, associations among households such as the Barangay Power Association (BAPA) demonstrate important local self-help initiatives. Most of these electricity services are carried out through specific project grants and are not akin to market-based partnerships.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fa7a6813-c667-4530-a8c6-75ebaa0fb2e0": {"__data__": {"id_": "fa7a6813-c667-4530-a8c6-75ebaa0fb2e0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in the Philippines", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6033c24a601ca624819ba788d7524e7d55a048660da1c871116016a09c5129f1"}, "2": {"node_id": "ead07269-3233-4dd3-bea0-380bede69ade", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Developme