 village to village. Moreover, sparsely populated islands and communities face neglect. The usual approach of expanding grid-based electrification cannot be sustained and needs fresh funding or other approaches that could reach the unviable 8 percent of barangays or 38 percent of the households, mostly in remote and poor communities. Gender equity too is also not well addressed in these programmes. Also, even though biomass is the predominant and highly dispersed fuel currently (and expected to be so in the future for rural and poor communities), there are The approach of expanding grid-based electrification cannot be sustained. Programmes, policies and strategies Programmes adopted Policies in relation to rural energy Strategies applied in the context of rural energy Early 1970s to mid-1990s National Electrification Administration's (NEA's) Rural Electrification Programme General policies or policy statements found in the 1987 Constitution3 The Philippine Environmental Code (1977)4 National Electrification Programme9 1999 Accelerated Barangay Electrification Programme The Medium Term Development Plan5 Department of Energy (DoE) Act of 19926 Energizing remaining communities through acceleration of NEA programmes10 2000 O\u2019Ilaw Programme1 Executive Order 2157 Providing energy services to communities with renewable energy (RE) technologies.11 2003 Expanded Rural Electrification Programme2 DoE Circular 2000-03-003, amending DoE Energy Regulations No. 1-94 on benefits to host communities8 Facilitate wider access to electricity;12 catalyse the market by allowing entry of different players13 2004 Private sector participation through qualified third parties (QTPs) Opening up of the provision of electricity to remote, unviable areas that cannot be served by franchised utilities to the private sector or QTPs. TABLE 2 PROGRAMMES, POLICIES AND STRATEGIES ADOPTED IN THE CONTEXT OF RURAL ELECTRICITY ACCESS FROM EARLY 1970S TO 2004 6 Expected results in rural electricity acce