, "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2fb411650e489f8999ed1e77152e58a24d2fe1cae94b1cbd8ffd3765e11a4edb"}, "3": {"node_id": "d4b23c2a-c6e4-4ef5-8858-1af0a9598cb5", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5c00a3009177a8ad6c5236fbecb3c9b02225820b7614912d870db20601fe7188"}}, "hash": "f357e8bfb4be29fab26c82ae3b1c2f1be97c816a2be2090c477e36df3992123a", "text": "for the formulation of the means of giving direct benefit to provinces, cities, or municipalities. This benefit especially holds for the community and people affected, and allots equitable preferential benefit to the affected region. 7 Allows the private sector to generate electricity. It provides that private entities construct and operate (among others) cogeneration units and electric generating plants. 8 It states that electrification funds from energy projects or energy-generating facilities may be ordered and allocated by DoE for appropriate energy projects that can provide immediate electrification to host local government units (LGUs) or regions. This will be applicable to areas where the grid-type is deemed unviable. Practical alternative sources shall be used, such as new and renewable energy technologies, with electricity generating potentials like solar energy, mini-hydro, biomass and so on. 9 Using franchise approach for electric cooperatives, distribution utilities and private independently owned utilities (PIOUs). 10 With active support from DoE\u2019s relevant units. 11 For example, solar photovoltaic home systems, micro-hydro, solar battery charging and so on. 12 Through connections of sitios (small communities) and households. 13 From the Government (NEA, PNOC-EIES, NPC-SPUG, DoE), independent power producers (IPPs), QTPs and PIOUs. 7 8 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES no promotional programmes overseeing its sustainable use. Devices such as energy-efficient stoves are not being seen, let alone the adoption of other clean technologies for biomass use. The programme framework for energy and poverty is influenced by challenges of policy and regulatory mechanisms. The current focus on electrification and market-based policies to improve competitiveness does not emphasize specific decentralization of the energy agenda. This is similar to the devolvement of services in health and other services. On the regulatory side, the Energy Regulatory Commission (ERC) has not yet developed guidelines on the Missionary Electrification (under the Electric Power Industry Reform Act [EPIRA]) regarding issues that are applicable to the energy and poverty linkage. There is no policy on the institutional arrangement for public\u2013private partnership. Many projects (such as Alliance for Mindanao Off-grid Renewable Energy [AMORE], Solar Power Technology Support [SPOTS] Project, Global Village Energy Project [GVEP], Asian Alliance of Appropriate Technology Practitioners [APPROTECH ASIA] and other bilateral ones) have been involved in public\u2013private partnership in energy services for communities. These have involved local groups in cooperation with NGOs and private companies that operate and maintain the energy systems in a sustainable manner. However, the policies have not promoted explicitly public\u2013private partnerships. Absence of synergy in policies that prevent conflicts between programmes, the lack of effective policy development to facilitate innovations and capacity development in energy service delivery continue. These coexist with other initiatives of the Government, such as the proposed enactment of an RE Bill that will provide basic policies for RE development and utilization. BOX 2 KEY CHALLENGES IN PROGRAMME FRAMEWORK P Instead of a Government-funded grid extension to electrify the remaining 8 percent of barangays, new approaches have become necessary. P Renewable energy technology is considered a viable alternative to grid electricity in remote barangays, but there is no specific programme promoting and supporting its use. Limited access to modern energy services in remote inland provinces and sparsely populated islands The objective of all energy- and poverty-related programmes in the Philippines is to provide equitable access to energy for all. Even in the 9 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES most optimistic projection, it is not viable for local electric cooperatives to extend their grids to the unserved areas in the next decade. The prohibitively high cost of electricity produced and distributed through small and inefficient generating sets with high fuel cost has also resulted in limited access to modern energy services in inland provinces and small sparsely populated islands. Access to energy for cooking in the Philippines has been limited by a shortage of supply and the high prices of energy in remote and sparsely populated islands. Most low-income households have little capacity to purchase modern energy, and instead rely heavily on firewood and biomass residues. Currently, the fuel requirements of 55 percent of the rural poor are met by firewood, with another 25 percent being met by biomass residues. Consumers buy kerosene and diesel at prices set by oil companies in a free market situation.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d4b23c2a-c6e4-4ef5-8858-1af0a9598cb5": {"__data__": {"id_": "d4b23c2a-c6e4-4ef5-8858-1af0a9598cb5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "exclu