zers, or feed \u2013 as fuels could deplete soil nutrients, and reduce agricultural and livestock productivity. Excessive dependence involves a trade-off in agricultural productivity. P Gathering fuel consumes time, which women and children could otherwise use more productively. P Rural development is hampered by the lack of modern energy supplies. The policy does not rule out the utilization of traditional energy services in rural areas. In fact, as projected, traditional fuels will continue to play a significant role in rural energy usage, with access to modern energy sources remaining very limited. Income-generating activities emphasize efforts to increase efficient utilization of available energy resources. Non-proximity to commercial markets creates an access barrier for services related to cooking and lighting energy for many communities in the country (Table 3). Those who are already purchasing liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) and kerosene (8 percent of the population), travel a distance of more than 5 kilometres. The situation is worse in far-flung, calamity-stricken areas that are hardly reached by commercial distribution networks. If at all, these fuels are expected to be unaffordable. TABLE 3 HOUSEHOLDS PURCHASING FUELS BY DISTANCE OF FUEL SOURCE Type of fuel / Distance of fuel source Number Percentage from residence of households Total households 16,640 000 100.0 Liquefied petroleum gas 8,617,000 51.8 Less than 250 m 5,061,000 58.7 Between 250 m and 1 km 1,961,000 22.8 Between 1 and 5 km 937,000 10.9 More than 5 km 657,000 7.6 Kerosene 9,319,000 56.0 Less than 250 m 6,073,000 65.2 Between 250 m and 1 km 1,417,000 15.2 Between 1 and 5 km 964,000 10.3 More than 5 km 864,000 9.3 Source NSO\u2013DoE (2004) 11 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES Lack of modern energy technology options Two major characteristics of energy systems in rural and unserved areas in the Philippines are (1) excessive dependence on biomass energy and (2) low efficiency i