dissemination and access to modern technology. The challenge is to consolidate and integrate different approaches by different sectors in a sustained programme, encouraging self-help and sustainable access to energy using modern technology options for the poor in rural and unserved areas. In general, these programmes have yet to be translated into practical policy guidelines and procedures, so that they can be understood at the local community and household levels. These guidelines and procedures should promote wider decentralization of modern energy services and facilitate decisions towards more efficient technologies. However, there is clearly an unwillingness on the part of rural households to spend additional resources on expensive appliances, no matter how efficient the technology is. BOX 4 KEY CHALLENGES TO ENERGY TECHNOLOGY EFFICIENCY P Excessive dependence on biomass energy and low efficiency in its use. P High prices prevent people from adopting efficient devices and fuels. P Local production of reliable, affordable and clean technologies and the provision of industry services are in the early stages of development. Therefore, imported technology/equipment and parts for solar, wind and biomass energy are still seen. Energy-based entrepreneurship concerns While there is no credible data on rural small and medium enterprises (SMEs), they are significant generators of income and employment in The affordability factor limits access to alternative energy technologies and efficient fuels. 13 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES rural areas. The growing need to improve livelihood opportunities for the rural poor is taking centre stage in the planning and development of decentralized energy-based entrepreneurship. In principle, almost all ongoing energy projects have articulated their intentions to promote energy-based entrepreneurship to develop rural areas, reduce poverty and promote gender equity. For instance, the Government has launched a programme to support new financial mechanisms (particularly microfinance) aimed at encouraging rural development through small enterprises. Several projects and organizations have also incorporated business aspects in rural energy services such as (1) Capacity Building for Removal of Barriers in Renewable Energy Development (CBRED) Project, (2) AMORE, (3) GVEP, (4) the World Bank\u2019s Rural Power Project (RPP), (5) SPOTS Project, (6) SIBAT, (7) Yamog Renewable Energy Development Group, Inc., (8) EIES Project (implemented by the Philippine National Oil Company) and (9) electrification of host communities by independent power producers. There is very limited information available on existing energy entrepreneurs in rural areas or even on the growth of SMEs and micro- enterprises in relation to energy service provision. Hence, the effectiveness of the Government initiatives in this regard is not clear. Issues of energy-based entrepreneurship can be classified into two, often overlapping and complementary, areas: (1) energy provision entrepreneurs and (2) energy- based enterprises. These two types of entrepreneurship can converge to provide more sustainable, reliable, accessible and affordable energy supply, together with other services. For example, the provision of electricity, ice and potable water is packaged as an enterprise. Thus, income-augmenting components of energy provision projects, along with energy providers and users, can improve financial capacity through effective management and creative entrepreneurship. The income level of entrepreneurs, the community and its households can be increased through the introduction of a business model that promotes productive uses of energy at the household and community levels. For electricity-providing entrepreneurs, the additional load from productive applications (brought in by energy-based small businesses) improves capacity utilization and load factors.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "