manufacturing facilities, potteries, bakeries, activities of blacksmiths and carpentry workshops. Shops and establishments that do not fall under either of these categories could be classified under the rural services sector. Energy usage for income-generating activities is often substantial and not always distinguishable from pure household consumption. The rural-energy-based entrepreneurs need energy for lighting, process heat, motive or shaft power, and increasingly need electricity for computers and communication. Lighting requirements are provided by electricity, either from the grid, diesel or gasoline generators, or kerosene (in power-less villages). Motive power requirements are met by electricity where it is available and by diesel engines or human labour using mechanical equipment, where electricity is unavailable. The principal supply sources of process heat for blacksmiths\u2019 work, brick-making and charcoal manufacture are fuelwood and other biomass. In agro-based facilities, the use of biomass is widespread. Access to finance for energy projects In the Philippines, the financing and banking sector has actively provided decentralized services for financing various rural-based development projects. Several Government and private banks have extended their The use of energy for income- generating activities in rural areas is often substantial. 15 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES lending programmes to rural development projects, including agriculture, home-based industries and energy services for poverty reduction. Energy project financing can take two forms: (1) energy provision (both at the national and local levels) and (2) energy use in households, communities and energy-based enterprises. Access to finance for conventional power plants is well established, but for new and RE facilities, financing windows are still being established. Increasing petroleum and conventional fuel prices and the introduction of RE incentives have increased competition in alternative energy projects. Innovative financing for cleaner and indigenous energy technology is now acceptable and entering various bank financing portfolios. Access to finance for energy use is less established and usually not practised. Packaging of energy projects that incorporate energy utilization and application has been initiated in some projects but, as mentioned above, there is a lack of demonstrable cases of viable financial mechanisms. Cases that have incorporated innovative business and service provisions with service delivery are still not the norm. Perhaps one of the most critical issues in rural energy development is the non-monetized nature of several aspects of the rural economy. Traditionally, the bulk of energy supplies comes in the form of wood and other biomass fuels. This has been considered a free source and many do not want to purchase it. At the same time, moving beyond the satisfaction of basic needs towards higher levels of economic productivity does mean the introduction of expensive modern energy sources into rural societies. However, the merits of the Government subsidies designed to accelerate substitution are debatable. Whether intended or not, it is inevitable that at least some of the subsidies will benefit the higher income strata and commercial establishments rather than disadvantaged households. This goes beyond households as their members venture into productive, entrepreneurial activities for livelihood and improvement of living conditions. Therefore, access to finance will be as important as access to energy. Comprehensive inventory of all existing and planned financial mechanisms is being made for alternative energy projects and other business areas by the CBRED Project. The energy provision projects are being viewed as a total marketing and financial package. For instance, the viability of a micro-hydro project can improve tremendously if financing is packaged with livelihood projects and income-generating businesses. On the other hand, certain financing mechanisms do exist for non-energy projects that are designed for the socio-economic development of Access to finance for energy use in households is less established. 16 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES BOX 6 KEY CHALLENGES IN ACCESSING FINANCE FOR ENERGY PROJECTS P Viable,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c68d0ccd-316c-4c08-a4d8-5cf3112e05d7": {"__data__": {"id_": "c68d0ccd-316c-4c08-a4d8-5cf3112e05d7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in the Philippines", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4b46c1b3bb9829c0fec24cd03efb18dd9a19b3c83409c46229ebfaa64cb09a41"}, "3": {"node_id": "8c290d99-6d51-4984-9a7e-fc341564ab61", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "adbde51507ca5e478a9da521c59788721116d4e8b0bb838c6f2ac6f4eac8c52d"}}, "hash": "5e41d5a1773a5c4bee02ac187609fc0271e3bc5f19ca339bb9251d9f50e0d0bc", "text": "workable financing models for entrepreneurial and private participation in rural energy service delivery are yet to be realized. P Weak decentralization levels to tackle rural energy finance and management concerns. P Unfriendly bank policies (such as collaterals, joint and several signatories and bank guarantees) act as an impediment towards growth of rural banking. P Roles/policies of public institutions towards financing energy access for poor communities not defined clearly, despite a general policy of poverty reduction in all sectors. P Absence of specific pricing policies for the provision of affordable energy to the poor results in unclear pricing. P Lack of modalities to establish a process of continuous assessment and improvement in concessions/subsidies, special purpose funds, promotion of microfinance, and inclusion of private investments. communities, with gender equity considerations. The surveys will also determine if the energy components or needs of these projects can be enhanced to provide entrepreneurial opportunities in energy service delivery. Several capacity-building programmes (with different aspects of financing rural development) are in place, particularly with microfinance and private sector financing participation. The Development Bank of the Philippines (DBP), the Land Bank, and other Government and private banks have ongoing programmes to train bank staff, private groups, and Government personnel in these areas. Though such initiatives establish the linkage between energy and poverty, capacity development programmes are dispersed across different projects. The DoE itself, through its CBRED Project, has initiated three pilot financing mechanisms. These are project development funding, loan guarantee and microfinance. They are meant to cater to RE development through designated banks as a means of building the capacity of the financial sector. Government financing institutions \u2013 such as the DBP, the Land Bank, and some local banks \u2013 and grant-funded projects, such as the one in Palawan, have also financed RE projects. The programme aims to decentralize financing facilities through selected programme managers who have a wide presence at the local level. In addition, through the CBRED Project, a compendium of available financial mechanisms for RE 17 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES development has been prepared. Another microfinance model has emerged from the Quedan and Rural Credit Guarantee Corporation better known as QUEDANCOR, the credit and guarantee agency of the Philippine Department of Agriculture (DoA). QUEDANCOR has committed to provide 25 million Philippine Pesos (US $0.5 million) in non-collateral, low-interest micro-loans for RE-powered livelihood projects of AMORE\u2019s beneficiary communities. QUEDANCOR has so far awarded livelihood micro-loans to 38 Barangay Renewable Energy and Community Development Association (BRECDA) members of the Tawi-Tawi. Financing for large-scale energy sector development is provided through public institutions that are influenced by policies of poverty reduction across all sectors. Private banks, primarily under social responsibility programmes and policies enacted by multilateral funding agencies, such as the Asian Development Bank (ADB), UNDP and the World Bank, too have direct funding arrangements for energy, poverty reduction and even gender equity issues. Regarding regulatory frameworks for energy financing, ERC is responsible for issuing regulations for all rate-setting proposals in energy-related projects and commercial energy service delivery. It is also responsible for approving petitions for Missionary Electrification. In terms of the cost of energy access, the absence of specific pricing policies for the provision of affordable energy services to the poor poses as a major obstacle. ERC has neither any pricing regulation for off-grid electricity, nor pricing methodologies that can serve as guidelines. For grid electrification, the prices are set at the level of electricity cooperative franchisees, while the NPC\u2013SPUG handles the modality of pricing electricity in missionary areas. Gender concerns in energy issues The emphasis on women\u2019s involvement in all programmes and projects \u2013 as well as the recognition of the need of their economic empowerment \u2013 is evident in the Government\u2019s pronouncements and the Medium-Term Philippine Development Plan (MTPDP). The Government has fully recognized the need to increase women\u2019s representation at the decision- making level in the Government, non-government and semi-government sectors. It also plans to monitor any gender discrimination at work. However, in spite of the incorporation of gender equity in the Government programmes, these do not link gender concerns with energy policy. If ever gender is considered, it mostly remains a separate component or a mere addendum, without any link to the main policy and programme documents. Guidelines have not been translated into action.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8c290d99-6d51-4984-9a7e-fc341564ab61": {"__data__": {"id_": "8c290d99-6d51-4984-9a7e-fc341564ab61", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in the Philippines", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4b46c1b3bb9829c0fec24cd03efb18dd9a19b3c83409c46229ebfaa64cb09a41"}, "2": {"node_id": "c68d0ccd-316c-4c08-a4d8-5cf3112e05d7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/p