rk, and performance indicators for energy and poverty for sectoral programmes It is necessary to examine the macro-economic indicators that explain the progress or effects of policies and programmes implemented towards achieving a synergy between energy access and poverty reduction. Since there is no comprehensive programme that links energy and poverty for rural areas, a corresponding monitoring and evaluation (M&E) system is also missing. Capacities are project-oriented and need to be consolidated into an integrated framework to undertake M&E and measure programmatic impacts. However, the energy sector needs specific indicators that tie its performance measures \u2013 to track the impact of access to energy on indicators of human development \u2013 for example, the MDG indicators. Ongoing projects have M&E systems to serve individual project requirements only, and local governments use a quantitative community- based monitoring system (CBMS). Indicators and benchmarks have been developed in the Philippines to monitor human development, but these apply to MDG-related activities. Monitoring the electrification of the number of municipalities, barangays and households, however, is not enough. It should be taken a step further to gauge the impact of electrification on income/human poverty reduction. Yet, despite the agencies having capacities to monitor performances in other developmental programmes, energy indicators are BOX 7 KEY CHALLENGES TO MONITORING AND EVALUATION P There are no M&E policies or indicators to integrate various sectoral goals with goals of affordable energy access to the rural poor. P Information on energy M&E is incomplete and inconsistent, with no modalities to share information across related agencies. P Energy services delivery indices are not yet consolidated into a unified framework/system. There are no indicators that link energy and poverty. 19 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES not considered in these M&E processes. There are no indicators that tie up energy and poverty issues with common development objectives in agriculture, industry, commerce, local government and other sectors. Absence of an integrated management information system pertaining to energy and poverty Since the nature of concerns surrounding MDGs and energy and poverty is rather comprehensive, the need for integrated management information systems (MIS) is significant. Many earlier sectoral initiatives \u2013 such as the CBRED Project \u2013 led to the development of an information database and access systems for RE. Yet, the access of energy professionals and consumers to information remains restricted in the Philippines. A reliable and timely database system is urgently needed. To make a start, DoE has initiated (through CBRED Project) the process of making databases available to various RE programme stakeholders. This comprehensive database will eventually be shared by various agencies involved in energy planning and implementation. The integrated MIS would ultimately cover all other sectors that bear relevance to energy and poverty. Rural communities, in particular, lack sufficient and timely information on issues such as traditional energy inefficiencies or financing schemes for energy installations. Additionally, the Government bodies and related agencies and NGOs have recorded their best practices and experiences in databases. However, there is no systematic integration of such databases. Positive developments towards the availability of information include modalities for knowledge sharing at the national, central and project levels. These are supported through different agencies, projects and programmes such as the CBRED Project, APPROTECH ASIA, GVEP, AMORE, World Bank\u2019s RPP and SPOTS Project. BOX 8 KEY CHALLENGES TO INFORMATION MANAGEMENT P Lack of a specific policy framework that enhances the existing state of energy information access. P Existing knowledge repositories on energy are inaccessible to municipal bodies and communities. P Lack of success stories about the contribution of modern technologies towards poverty reduction or addressing gender concerns. Rural communities, in particular, lack sufficient and timely information. 20 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES A parent agency for issues related to energy and poverty E fforts to align the energy sector with poverty reduction programmes must begin at the central institutional level. If poverty reduction objectives and activities are dispersed in different agencies without an integral platform, the performance measures, resource pooling and desired results too will get dispersed. For this purpose, a coordinating mechanism with definite roles and responsibilities needs to be established to align the activities of the Government agencies and corporations mandated to provide energy services, livelihood promotions, rural development, gender equity and other aspects needed for poverty reduction. Depending on the institutional policy that will be adopted, this coordinating role could be played by existing institutions with related responsibility for poverty reduction or energy sector development", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fdcd53c2-a103-40c5-b4ab-eeec018d3d7a": {"__data__": {"id_": "fdcd53c2-a103-40c5-b4ab-eeec018d3d7a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in the Philippines", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "407e3b1c3b448d2d8c33b285efb1439f9777a95c2b9a2cc753d13982a3d36c44"}}, "hash": "407e3b1c3b448d2d8c33b285efb1439f9777a95c2b9a2cc753d13982a3d36c44", "text": "(such as NAPC and DoE). Since these institutions have their own specific mandates to fulfil, it may be necessary to designate a focal agency at the national level, which could integrate policies, programmes and activities on rural energy access and poverty reduction. The National Economic and Development Authority (NEDA) \u2013 which is also in charge of unifying the MDG programme for the country \u2013 is an appropriate focal agency for this mission. At the local level, specific plans and roles and responsibilities for local government units (LGUs) can be defined to address the challenges of energy and poverty. NGOs, people\u2019s organizations (POs) and the civil society \u2013 in partnership with local cooperatives \u2013 could also be involved. In this context, the environment is already conducive for public\u2013private partnerships, such as on-grid power generation where private qualified third parties (QTPs) are allowed to operate in franchise-waived areas. Incorporating livelihood concerns into the programme framework The Government of the Philippines will need to reassess the national energy programming/strategy framework to incorporate poverty reduction objectives and targets into rural energy programmes. By incorporating income-generating livelihood, energy provision projects and energy-based businesses help improve operating load factors and viability of power plants. Programmes and institutional structures to implement such enterprises will need to be established. The same will also be needed for non-power energy provision, as it will boost efficiency of traditional cooking and heating fuels. Significant momentum has been gained through the Missionary Electrification Programme, the RE MEETING THE CHALLENGES A coordinating mechanism with definite roles and responsibilities needs to be established. 21 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES Commercialization Programme and the RE policy framework. The private sector funded investment programmes on RE are geared specifically for income generation in coastal, lowland and upland barangays. These involve the provision of heat, mechanical energy and electricity to increase economic productivity in rural communities. Additionally, hybrid power systems using a combination of diesel and RE are also being considered for villages on small islands. Such initiatives will require adequate policy and financial support. Funding can be sourced from the universal charge as authorized by EPIRA. Similarly, to address the uncontrolled use of biomass for fuel needs, DoE has put in place an \u2018Adopt a Programme\u2019 framework. This has been done in cooperation with relevant agencies such as the Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR), the Forest Products Development Company, DoA and the Department of Interior and Local Government to grow trees in managed plantations for fuelwood. This programme could be extended to include the development or adoption of cleaner technology that uses fuelwood efficiently. Improving energy access in rural and unserved areas Many projects \u2013 such as those initiated by APPROTECH ASIA, GVEP, SPOTS Project, EIES Project, AMORE, and others \u2013 have demonstrated, to varying degrees, that energy access provision to rural and unserved areas can result in improved socio-economic development. This can be further enhanced through increased or improved energy use in small businesses, productive uses of energy in agriculture, home-based livelihoods and community-based projects, as well as for common social uses in schools, health centres, public places and for street lighting. DoE already employs several mechanisms to ensure that access to energy can be improved in rural and unserved areas. The modality employed is through the realization of its Expanded Rural Electrification Programme\u2019s goal of total electrification of barangays by 2008. It is necessary to consolidate and integrate such approaches, and encourage self-help and sustainability for energy access to the poor in areas without electricity. Creating a local manufacturing base for energy technologies The focus on improving access to modern energy necessitates a simultaneous push towards newer, cleaner and affordable energy systems. Since considerable progress has been achieved in the RE sector, it is logical for the country\u2019s energy planners to further the gains by extending the reach of RE systems and tapping their livelihood MEETING THE CHALLENGES 22 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES enhancement potential. One way of achieving this is by developing a local manufacturing base for RE equipment, a process that has been initiated by DoE through the CBRED Project. It is important, however, that large-scale RE technology options do not overshadow other small-scale technology improvements needed for efficient use of energy, in particular improved cook stoves (ICS). It is possible to reduce fuelwood consumption for cooking by 50 percent through the use of ICS, which will not only save energy costs for low- income families, but also halt excessive exploitation of forest land and provide health benefits. In this context, multilateral and bilateral agencies with extensive experience in ICS can", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "91ec2e97-5088-4c7e-a436-f0b4579f2e85": {"__data__": {"id_": "91ec2e97-5088-4c7e-a436-f0b4579f2e85", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in the Philippines", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-philippines", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7b2c8d36a64895aab0b0dafece21fc2c87a6b25f67174baead78ab77777abbf2"}}, "hash": "7b2c8d36a64895aab0b0dafece21fc2c87a6b25f67174baead78ab77777abbf2", "text": "aid the ongoing ICS programme launched by the Department of Health in 10 provinces. Bolstering financial support for rural energy supply and demand The extent of decentralization to address rural energy finance and its management must be further reinforced at the community and household levels. This is essential, for modern energy is to play a larger role in rural development. A model of decentralization is already available in the RE microfinance facility for DoE to expand. An additional area of focus will be a demonstration of the business viability of rural energy service delivery, in an effort to attract private investment in rural energy projects. The Philippines also requires policy guidelines for financing schemes. These guidelines will have to be considerate towards the needs, paying capacity, income-generating pattern and other related factors of its consumers. DoE, in collaboration with the Department of Finance, can issue such guidelines. Finally, electricity tariffs can be re-evaluated and modified (where possible) to make the tariff structure pro-poor. Since ERC develops pricing schemes with DoE\u2019s assistance, both agencies could consider pricing modalities such as the one practised by the Tulong sa Karunungan Institute (TSKI). At TSKI, the \u2018seasonality\u2019 of revenues of farmers is used as a guide. Therefore, rates are higher during harvesting months as compared to those in the lean months. Encouraging energy-based entrepreneurship To devise effective interventions in order to boost modern energy use in rural industries, the Philippines needs a system to capture relevant information to keep track of SMEs and micro-enterprises in rural areas. In this context, DoE will need to mandate all energy programmes (with MEETING THE CHALLENGES Financing scheme guidelines will have to be considerate towards the needs, paying capacity and income- generating pattern. 23 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES linkages to SME development) to document, and report best practices and lessons learnt at the national and local levels. At the policy level, the RE Bill, which is in the final stages of legislation \u2013 along with other policies \u2013 can be further reviewed to explore how these can be harmonized as a common set of policies. Such an initiative will help implement rules and regulations to promote decentralized energy-based entrepreneurship. A monitoring and evaluation framework for energy and poverty, inclusive of community-based activities The efficacy of modern energy towards achieving poverty reduction can be assessed only if a systematic M&E system is in place. Such a system should include performance indicators and benchmarks to track the impact of energy services on poverty reduction and gender equity. Additionally, since the impact of energy on poverty can be better observed at the local level, a CBMS (currently being used by local governments) can act as a platform to monitor energy- and poverty- related projects at the community level. Suitable baseline data and indicators must be built into the system design. Indicators could be aligned to MDGs and integrated with inter- sectoral objectives, along with with the following. P Percentage of households connected P Percentage of population with access to electricity and petroleum fuels P Number of barangays with common energy services for street lighting, barangay hall, hospitals and assembly areas P Energy used and their share in productive application P Volume of fuelwood and other biomass used, and their sources of supply P Literacy level in electrified and unelectrified areas P Prevalence of smoke-related respiratory diseases in barangays P Number of livelihood projects established through modern energy provision Building management information systems Increasing access to energy and development-related information will aid policy-makers in understanding issues of energy and poverty, and also help communities choose their energy options wisely. The information component of each sectoral programme could be incorporated into an integrated MIS. For instance, the CBRED Project can be useful in laying the foundation of information access, starting from the RE database and exchange system that is being developed. Information access (specific to MEETING THE CHALLENGES 24 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES linkages between energy and poverty) can be expanded along with M&E systems to achieve MDGs and other inter-sectoral action plans. With increased accessibility of information systems, the exchange of information covering the broad concerns of energy and poverty can be facilitated. CONCLUSION CONCLUSION Priority agenda for action T he proposed critical measures need to be integrated within policies, programmes, institutional structures and their coordinating mechanisms among energy and related socio-economic agencies and participating groups. In the short term, the designation of a parent focal agency and establishment of coordinating mechanisms at the central and local levels hold priority. Among its primary responsibilities, it will need to tackle the issues of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a449570a-616c-4484-a53d-f75