ic institutional arrangements, national energy policies and regulatory frameworks, which that define roles and responsibilities at the national and local levels to create the necessary economic, social and institutional conditions in the energy sector. P Promote sustainable use of fuelwood and other biomass resources and \u2013 as and where appropriate \u2013 other REs (through the use of productive management of resources, efficient use of fuels and provision of new or improved energy products, services and technologies). P Support the transition to modern, cleaner uses of kerosene, electricity and LPG, where they are considered environmentally and socially acceptable and cost-effective. 25 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES P Enhance access to reliable, affordable, socially acceptable and environment-friendly energy services as an integral part of poverty reduction programmes. P Strengthen public\u2013private partnerships, including civil society, NGOs, POs, investors, industries, regulators, financial institutions, communities, LGUs and other potential stakeholders. P Undertake awareness and advocacy programmes on energy policies and plans targeted at policy-makers, Government officials, private entrepreneurs, social workers, consumers, NGOs, and people in development committees to encourage their participation in the planning process for a decentralized, participatory approach. Capacity development P Improve capability to supply and access reliable, affordable, socially acceptable and environment-friendly energy services and resources. P Intensify agricultural productivity and promote non-farm livelihood activities through SMEs, including household-based activities and micro-enterprises. P Establish capacity to effectively implement financial and technological assistance and innovative financing mechanisms at the household and community levels. P Estimate and plan required investments at the local, regional and national levels, including those needed for universal electricity access for the poor. P Identify suitable financial resources and mechanisms to meet the investment requirements and operating costs at the above- mentioned levels. Knowledge management P Improve access to knowledge repositories to promote adoption of modern biomass technologies and fuelwood sources and supplies, and commercialize biomass operations. P Urgently assist and facilitate the access of the rural poor to knowledge on reliable, affordable and environment-friendly energy services, with financial and technical assistance from developed country partners, multilateral institutions, and public\u2013private partnerships. P Facilitate the dissemination of best practices and success stories of local NGOs and organizations on energy services. P Carry out relevant data collection and analysis, gather case studies, document relevant RE and clean fuel technologies, and assess energy resources and infrastructures. CONCLUSION SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES 26 27 SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES (CONTINUED...) SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES (CONTINUED...) 28 29 SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES (CONTINUED...) 30 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES (CONTINUED...) 30 31 Energy and Poverty in the Philippines THE CHALLENGES REFERENCES IEA (International Energy Agency). 2006 International Energy Agency Statistics 2006 Selected 2004 Indicators for Philippines Available at <http://www.iea.org/Textbase/stats/index.asp>, last accessed on 28 December 2006 NEDA (National Economic and Development Authority). 2004 Second Philippines Progress Report on the Millennium Development Goals Pasig City, The Philippines: NEDA NSO\u2013DoE (National Statistics Office and Department of Energy). 2