nd Poverty in Pacific Island Countries: Challenges and the Way Forward Other publications from Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction 1. Overcoming Vulnerability to Rising Oil Prices: Options for Asia and the Pacific 2. Will Tomorrow be Brighter than Today? Addressing Gender Concerns in Energy for Poverty Reduction in the Asia-Pacific Region 3. Delivering Energy Services for Poverty Reduction: Success Stories from Asia and the Pacific 4. Cross Border Energy Trade and its Impacts on the Poor 5. Financing Options for Renewable Energy: The Asia-Pacific Experience The UNDP Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) aims to affect broad-based interventions in the energy sector focusing on Asia Pacific countries. The emphasis is on harnessing energy effectively to meet developmental targets laid out in the Millennium Devel- opment Goals. As a first step to achieve the objectives of REP-PoR, this publica- tion reports on the Philippines\u2019s energy sector and its linkages to poverty con- cerns, gaps therein, and modalities for overcoming the same. It aims to facilitate the inclusion of a strong energy compo- nent into the Philippines\u2019s socio-eco- nomic development programmes.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "43b8e438-bbaf-4a46-b2f6-fbb78df3c0ab": {"__data__": {"id_": "43b8e438-bbaf-4a46-b2f6-fbb78df3c0ab", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "afd45b55bef5cb1325ce4475d6b33ab18cb4fa7b3b94cbd90df7795e815c6309"}, "3": {"node_id": "eb2d2e44-ebd6-4116-83ce-7326952d6aea", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "43bd3e10597df281b8d26e724b11d278632c37753187a424d4c7ee74075b84cd"}}, "hash": "1ea1cb8f1eb422c538f30b61580680c653c441749d95b266adb7230df18f3f5d", "text": "Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Challenges and the Way Forward ENERGY AND POVERTY IN VIET NAM iv Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam Design and layout: Keen Media (Thailand) Co., Ltd. Cover images: UNDP-Viet Nam The analysis and policy recommendations of this report do not necessarily reflect the views of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), its executive board or its member states. The report is an independent publication commissioned by UNDP. It is the fruit of a collaborative effort by a team of eminent experts, stakeholders and the Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) team of the Regional Centre in Bangkok. Copyright \u00a9 2007 UNDP United Nations Development Programme Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok UN Service Building Rajdamnern Nok Avenue Bangkok 10200 Thailand http://regionalcentrebangkok.undp.or.th http://regionalcentrebangkok.undp.or.th/practices/energy_env/rep-por ISBN-13: 978-92-1-126192-9 Assigned Sales #: E.06.III.B.7 v Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam FOREWORD More than a billion people in the Asia-Pacific region do not have access to electricity and 1.7 billion are dependent on traditional biomass fuels for their cooking and heating needs. Access to affordable modern energy services can improve their productivity and enhance living standards. Even so, there are no specific targets for the energy sector in the Millennium Declaration, a historic document signed seven years ago by the world\u2019s leaders. Affordable and sustainable modern energy services are a necessity for countries to meet their Millennium Development Goals (MDGs). Efforts of countries in the Asia-Pacific region to meet these aims will be hindered unless adequate attention is given to the crucial role energy services play in the development process. This is particularly true for the economic, environmental and social well-being of the poor. With fluctuating energy prices, the poor in many of the countries in the Asia-Pacific region face a daunting future. For them, access to affordable and essential modern energy services that could improve their living conditions and ensure a means to earn a living will fall outside their reach. Recognizing the urgency for countries to factor in access to modern energy services, particularly when shaping national poverty reduction initiatives, the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) provided technical and financial support for national-level rapid energy assessments. The primary aim of this work, carried out through UNDP\u2019s Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) and completed in 2006, was to identify gaps and priority needs in linking energy services provision with poverty reduction. The framework for rapid gap assessments linking energy and poverty was developed as a joint effort of the UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok (RCB) and UNDP country offices in the region, with the support of experts from the region. The draft framework was discussed at two sub-regional meetings, one held in Bangkok, Thailand (August 2005) and the other in Apia, Samoa (September 2005). The meetings were helpful in customizing the framework to suit specific needs and circumstances of the participating countries. Subsequently, UNDP country offices held national-level stakeholder consultations to consolidate the findings and recommendations of the assessments. This work benefited immensely from the support of government vi Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam officials and representatives of civil society. Documented in individual country reports, this work serves as resource and reference material for programming and planning for access to modern energy services for the underserved, particularly, the poor. This document is a summary of the Country Report on Viet Nam and is part of a series of REP-PoR\u2019s Asia-Pacific publications. It draws on the key findings of the Country Report, summarizes the challenges faced at the national level, and provides priority recommendations. Specifically, critical issues related to energy policy, including institutional structures, regulatory frameworks, priority programmes, financing measures, gender concerns, as well as monitoring and evaluation support are highlighted. It offers a way forward, outlining issues and options for the country. Our hope is that this document will be of relevance to national policy makers, development partners, energy service providers, civil society organizations and academia in implementing various measures to promote access to modern energy services for the poor. Marcia V.J.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "eb2d2e44-ebd6-4116-83ce-7326952d6aea": {"__data__": {"id_": "eb2d2e44-ebd6-4116-83ce-7326952d6aea", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "afd45b55bef5cb1325ce4475d6b33ab18cb4fa7b3b94cbd90df7795e815c6309"}, "2": {"node_id": "43b8e438-bbaf-4a46-b2f6-fbb78df3c0ab", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1ea1cb8f1eb422c538f30b61580680c653c441749d95b266adb7230df18f3f5d"}}, "hash": "43bd3e10597df281b8d26e724b11d278632c37753187a424d4c7ee74075b84cd", "text": "Marcia V.J. Kran Head of Policy and Programmes UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok vii Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam This report sets out to examine the ways and means to providing affordable, accessible and reliable energy services in support of achievement of the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) and poverty reduction in Viet Nam. The underlying premise of this study is that access to affordable and sustainable sources of energy has strong links to poverty reduction. This is particularly the case in terms of energy and its effects on household income, health,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "784695d7-d8e1-4668-a918-ad5eca06b64d": {"__data__": {"id_": "784695d7-d8e1-4668-a918-ad5eca06b64d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4398b2937d5d3c82d784baf7ddc78744affd5e279a8dc4ba5126c7f13838ff4d"}}, "hash": "4398b2937d5d3c82d784baf7ddc78744affd5e279a8dc4ba5126c7f13838ff4d", "text": "education, gender and the environment. The report also offers options for the country to overcome its energy sector challenges. Over the last decade, poverty has decreased significantly in Viet Nam. In addition, households with access to electricity doubled during 1992-2004, from 48.9 to 90.5 percent. However, there is still a strong economic disparity between urban and rural poverty and a gap between urban and rural access to electricity. Poverty rates in remote, inaccessible areas, such as in mountainous regions and the highlands, are still particularly high. Low income households are highly dependent on affordable but inefficient and unsustainable sources of energy for most domestic and productive uses. Non-commercial biomass consumption includes firewood, charcoal and agro-residues and contributes to up to two-thirds of the national total energy consumption and up to 92 percent of the total rural thermal energy consumption for cooking, heating and food processing. In 2004, while almost all urban households were grid-connected, only 88 percent of the rural areas were connected. This study examines critical energy issues in Viet Nam related to the institutional structure of the energy sector, policy and regulatory framework and sectoral programmes. It analyses reasons for the limited reach of energy services to rural provinces; unsustainable dependence on traditional fuels and inefficient technologies; the limited supply of energy by rural energy enterprises; and inadequate financing for energy. Gender concerns are also examined in rural energy projects and programmes. It highlights the urgent need for key data and indicators to support monitoring and evaluation of energy access for areas that are least served. This report concludes that rural energy provision does not receive enough attention from state energy corporations, which are the main players with a near-monopoly status in energy service provision. Also, PREFACE viii Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam capacities to develop integrated rural energy plans are insufficient. Since Electricity of Viet Nam (EVN) does not reach the household level in rural areas, other players such as cooperatives, private enterprises, and joint ventures between local investors and state-owned companies are allowed to invest and operate in the communes. However, the regulatory framework for rural energy services is not sufficiently transparent and enforcement of tariff and quality standards is inadequate. Furthermore, these non-state rural energy service providers often have insufficient technical and financial capacities to manage the commune grid properly. Consequently, affordability and quality of service to end-users in rural areas remain as major constraints to the creation of a comprehensive pro-poor energy strategy in Viet Nam. In addition, no particular institution focuses on provision of traditional, non-electric energy services to rural areas. This study recommends that corporate entities should be given a greater role to cover remote areas and deprived communities. Speedy implementation of institutional reforms with a clear demarcation of responsibilities could help facilitate provision of modern energy services to low income households and set out terms of delivery and pricing for their benefit. Enforcement of guidelines for commune grid development and technical capacities of EVN and its subsidiaries could be mobilized and enhanced. Lack of institutional focus on rural energy provision for poverty alleviation and decentralization can be further addressed by developing capacity to use tools and frameworks towards planning integrated rural energy development, while also taking into account poverty reduction initiatives. Seeking cross-sectoral synergy could also help reduce dependence on biomass energy for cooking and disseminate widely technological solutions (e.g. improved cook stoves) for increasing efficiency of cooking fuel use and minimizing self-supply of such rural traditional energy types. Encouraging experiences in the energy sector can and do exist in Viet Nam. The sustained policy focus of the Government of Viet Nam on rural electrification is highly commendable. The Rural Electrification Programme (REP) was launched in 1996 to achieve the national goal of doubling electricity access by 2010. REP received assistance from all levels in terms of organizations, finance, planning and resource mobilization and is managed by EVN. After the programme was initiated, education and health care have improved due to the availability of energy services. The availability of motive power for irrigation, industries, handicrafts, agricultural product processing and income-generating opportunities has also increased. REP has improved access to electricity in almost all ix Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam provinces and regions. However, by limiting the scope at the commune centre, rather than reaching out to the households, the impact of REP on poverty is limited since it does not help the poor directly benefit from policies on preferential electricity pricing. Thus the gap between the poor and the rich regarding benefits of present rural electricity services remains. Subsidies at the national and local levels form the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9fd4fff8-1f31-42ea-8de1-7357a7e4f5ad": {"__data__": {"id_": "9fd4fff8-1f31-42ea-8de1-7357a7e4f5ad", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b2183eb0c02a2a02ac47284c08dd4fbe506a46bb37dcdc789a4233683ba4d742"}}, "hash": "b2183eb0c02a2a02ac47284c08dd4fbe506a46bb37dcdc789a4233683ba4d742", "text": "current mechanism for enabling access to rural energy services for poverty reduction and gender equality. However, despite government subsidies, electricity prices are still unaffordable for weaker sections of rural communities, leading to low consumption levels in rural households. Equally important is that energy services delivery is followed up to the household level, ensuring that the poor also benefit directly, and if they do not, the gaps need to be assessed and addressed. Programmes targeting improved rural energy access that focus on a wide range of energy types should be established in order to accelerate the accomplishment of these goals. These government- supported activities must be complemented, however, with additional strong recognition and efforts towards the goal of enhanced off-grid electrification and correcting unsustainable uses of fuelwood. The renewable energy development programme and the rural cooking fuel programme should be given more emphasis at the national level. We trust that the report is unique in terms of its insights into the current functioning of the energy sector and into options that bridge the gaps between access to energy and poverty reduction in Viet Nam. Our aim is to provide country specific information on institutional structures, energy resources, policy recommendations, and capacity and financial gaps that can point the way towards improving access to modern energy services, particularly for the poor. Nandita Mongia Regional Programme Coordinator and Team Leader Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok xi Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam: Challenges and the Way Forward is the result of a partnership initiative of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) Asia-Pacific Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR). It benefits from collaboration between the UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok (RCB), UNDP-Viet Nam Country Office, key national stakeholders and regional experts. This report is the eighth in the series of nine country reports for Asia and a synthesis report on similar lines for the Pacific Island countries. Like any multi-stakeholder work, this report reflects the efforts of many people over the last two years. We would like to express our appreciation for the inputs, suggestions and support provided by them. Our sincere appreciation goes to the excellent support of the Energy and Environment Team of UNDP-Viet Nam in the entire process of the gap assessment and the preparation of the original Country Report. The UNDP Country Office focal point in Viet Nam, Le Van Hung, provided strong support through many rounds of review and comments, in addition to providing critical data and information to complete this report. We appreciate the consistent support received from Nguyen Ngoc Ly, the Assistant Resident Representative of UNDP-Viet Nam all through this exercise. We convey our profound gratitude to key experts and officials of the Directorate for Provincial Industry (Ministry of Industry), the Institute of Energy (Viet Nam Electrics Corporation), the Agriculture and Rural Development Bank (AgriBank), the Viet Nam Women\u2