fcc25b4", "text": "Over the last decade, poverty has decreased significantly in Viet Nam, but there is still a strong economic disparity between urban and rural poverty, with a majority of lower income households living in rural areas. A human development index score of 0.709 ranked Viet Nam 109th out of 177 countries in 2004 (UNDP 2006). Poverty rates in remote, inaccessible areas, such as in mountainous regions and the highlands, are still high, primarily among some ethnic minority groups. The incidence of poverty is often high among communities in rural areas, where access to energy, availability of Capital Hanoi Area 331,114 square kilometres Population (2007) 86.4 million Total Primary Energy Supply/Population (2004) 0.61 toe/capita Gross domestic product (GDP) (2004) 41.25 billion US$ 2000 Energy Production (2004) 65.27 Mtoe Poverty rate (2004) Total: 24.1 % Rural: 27.5 % Urban: 10.8 % Traditional fuel consumption (2003) 23.3 % of total energy requirements Electricity consumption/Population (2004) 501 kWh/capita Net Imports (2004) - 14.34 Mtoe GDP per unit of energy use (2003) 4.4 US$ 2000 PPP per kg of oil equivalent CO2/Population (2004) 0.96 t CO2/capita BACKGROUND 2 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam BACKGROUND FIGURE 1 HOUSEHOLD ENERGY USE BY TYPE OF FUEL AND INCOME GROUPS Source GSO (2000) employment and provision of infrastructure are often lower than in urban areas. Past and current poverty assessments show that despite the overall reduction to 24 percent nation-wide, the poverty rate in rural areas continues to be three to six times higher than that in urban areas (GoV 2005). A recent survey shows that in some remote communities, the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "12b89369-0900-4570-aec7-fb9ec78c4e2c": {"__data__": {"id_": "12b89369-0900-4570-aec7-fb9ec78c4e2c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ce83367acfd4a6183ae97f40297cfc6ee3ae985010eca7e0b58fa14ffe6854a6"}, "3": {"node_id": "cd303e5e-3344-483c-b6b4-737983f8158c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9b718fb92971b5ded0a3251e3182771f6ee1b59bded8d540196f3cd0f967c172"}}, "hash": "b1a80ed90505b526fbd99311160f6f541b48ff626db6e7010f19bdf31c67871c", "text": "poverty rate is as high as 90 percent (World Bank 2003). The development of a modern energy sector, in general, and for the rural areas, in particular, is considered a prerequisite for socio-economic development and poverty reduction. Viet Nam\u2019s energy use patterns for lower income households indicate high dependence on affordable yet inefficient and unsustainable sources of energy for most domestic and productive uses. Non-commercial energies consumed in Viet Nam are mainly types of biomass, including firewood, charcoal and agro-residues (e.g. rice straws, rice husk and bagasse). The popular usages are for household cooking and rural small scale economic activities. This category contributes to up to two-thirds of the national total energy consumption (Thang 2003). In 1998, more than 92 percent of households in rural Viet Nam depended on fuelwood for cooking and heating (Figure 1). In 2004, for lighting purposes, kerosene was used by 11.6 percent of the lower income households1. The use of cleaner fuels such as liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) for cooking faces similar barriers of accessibility and affordability. 1 GSO website at: http://www.gso.gov.vn/default.aspx? tabid=417&idmid=4&ItemID =4284. This report uses the most updated data available from the General Statistical Office (GSO), as of November 2007. 3 BACKGROUND Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam THE CHALLENGES TABLE 1 MAJOR RESPONSIBILITIES AND ACTIVITIES OF MINISTRIES RELATED TO RURAL ENERGY Strong government control of institutional arrangements nstitutional reforms within Viet Nam\u2019s energy sector have taken place since the mid-1990s to achieve various goals: (1) speed up growth and access to modern energy; (2) improve corporate governance and market structures; and (3) strengthen regulatory frameworks and governance in the energy sector (World Bank 1999). In the 1990s, foreign direct investment was permitted in energy production, as well as in the distribution of electricity and LPG. The reforms established a number of state corporations that took over business operations from the line ministries, even though the ministries are still involved in planning, investment and development of regulatory frameworks and policies (Table 1). In addition, the State Pricing Committee, a subordinate to the Prime Minister\u2019s Office, has a crucial role in setting and adjusting prices for commercial energy, and providing information and advice to the Prime Minister. Ministry Responsibility Ministry of Industry (MoI) \u2022 Controls rural electrification programmes, development of renewable energy, electricity, research and development (R&D) of new energy sources, including renewable energy development, energy subsidy policies and prices \u2022 Enforces regulations on quality and efficiency of electricity services \u2022 Works with the State Pricing Committee to set tariffs for electricity and coal \u2022 Controls the production of petroleum products (mainly crude oil and natural gas) and coal Ministry of Trade (MoT)* \u2022 Controls oil imports, including petrol, diesel, kerosene and LPG \u2022 Intervenes in the rural energy service through its mandate to regulate domestic prices through fuel tariffs and distribution networks Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (MARD) \u2022 Controls forestry and rural development \u2022 Is responsible for government investment in areas that are primary sources of traditional biomass energy in rural households \u2022 Develops plantations for fuelwood \u2022 Coordinates the national 5 million hectare afforestation programme \u2022 Plays a strong potential role in regulating and promoting modern biomass energy in rural areas \u2022 Coordinates the national five-year social economic development plan and longer-term plans that link poverty reduction, social development and economic growth Ministry of Planning and Investment (MoPI) I 4 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam THE CHALLENGES TABLE 1 MAJOR RESPONSIBILITIES AND ACTIVITIES OF MINISTRIES RELATED TO RURAL ENERGY (CONTINUED) * A merge of MoI and MoT took place in June 2007. TABLE 2 MAJOR RESPONSIBILITIES AND ACTIVITIES OF ENERGY SERVICE PROVIDERS IN THE RURAL AREAS The biggest change resulting from the sectoral reforms is the increase in the number of energy service providers, including, on a limited scale, within the private sector (international and domestic). However, the institutional arrangement is still under stringent government control. State energy corporations are main players and have gained a near- monopoly status in energy service provision. The roles of some of these players are provided in Table 2. However, their focus on rural energy provision, in general, and poverty reduction, in particular, has been inadequate.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_templat