he retail market of vehicle and other oil fuels, it accounts for 70 percent of imported oil products; the rest belong to other corporations, such as Sai Gon Petroleum Import \u2013 Export Corporation, Petro Viet Nam Trading Corporation (PETECHIM) and Kerosene Import and Export Corporation (KEROCIMEX). 5 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam THE CHALLENGES TABLE 3 DECENTRALIZATION OF ELECTRICITY MANAGEMENT/ DISTRIBUTION The Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (MARD) (including forestry) has not actively considered agricultural residues, husbandry residues and fuelwood as traditional energies which meet most energy needs of poor households. Moreover, MARD is hardly involved in activities of capacity-building for its staff to better manage and use calculation tools and methods of integrated rural energy planning, even though it plays a key role in production and use of traditional biomass products that serve rural households, especially the poor (fuelwood and crop residues for cooking, such as rice straws, rice husks, bagasse, animal excrement for biogas production, etc.). Non-state providers of energy services in the rural areas are recognized in three major forms: (1) cooperatives; (2) private enterprises; and (3) joint ventures between local investors and state-owned companies. International non-governmental organizations (INGOs) provide energy services (biogas and improved cook stoves) for lower income households. Multilateral and bilateral donors have contributed significantly to Electricity of Viet Nam\u2019s (EVN\u2019s) Rural Electrification Programme (REP). At the local level, the role of the Provincial People\u2019s Committee in energy services is limited to the REP. The Commune Electricity Board model, in which the Commune People\u2019s Committee gives full rights to private contractors to deliver electricity services, is dominant in 65 to 70 percent of communes that have electrification (EVN 2005). For meeting energy needs beyond the electricity sector, state-owned companies manage wholesale and retail systems for coal and petroleum products through a partial government subsidy in isolated areas as a way to reduce poverty in ethnic communities and small commercial networks in communes that do not have access to roads (Table 3). Body Role Commune Electricity Board An autonomous body nominated by the commune authority to distribute electricity to households from the nearest transformer Private distributors/ sub-contractors Private investors selected to manage the commune grid Rural Electric Company Buys electricity from EVN and distributes it to commune households Provincial Water/ Electric Board Assigned by the Provincial People\u2019s Committee to operate the commune grid Commune Electricity Cooperative A commune-level, elected cooperative body to operate the commune grid on a non-profit basis 6 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam THE CHALLENGES Policy and regulatory framework The goal of electricity services in Viet Nam, as defined by the Government, is to achieve adequate provision of electricity in order to meet the demand for industrialization and modernization in lighting, thermal processing and motive usage for households, agriculture, industry, construction and transportation. According to the Government\u2019s plan, 100 percent of communes and 95 percent of rural households shall be provided with electricity services by 2010. It is anticipated that by 2015, the rate of households having access to electricity will reach 98 percent. The key policy areas related to the provision of electricity include: \u2022 Mechanism management for rural electric provision; \u2022 Development and renovation of rural grid; and \u2022 Electricity pricing regulation for different users: industrial, household, rural and urban. To address these areas, various policies and regulations have been developed and adjusted over the years. However, attracting private investments for rural electrification and enhancing public-private partnerships in the development of rural electricity services delivery have resulted in a regulatory framework in rural electricity services delivery to the non-governmental sections (commune electricity boards, electricity contractors, etc.) that is not formulated based on laws and transparency. Therefore, complying with agricultural and rural preferential electricity tariffs for poverty alleviation is not sufficiently controlled.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "67d3a69e-361a-4edf-a5bd-2a73f6446c88": {"__data__": {"id_": "67d3a69e-361a-4edf-a5bd-2a73f6446c88", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3ac85beada8083de6cd6bd526d598edd2e364456127a73d37f97486b9607fa30"}, "2": {"node_id": "5cddaaa1-3011-4afa-8c61-1d91e99b7b79", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c55e32a744186526ead78f6f02e55f1867aec9aa86c374b2c36e6914be56c887"}}, "hash": "584b435c79f02f84d1cb3f2683cb4781f04621a0cd153cd25dfce005a20f2614", "text": "Therefore, complying with agricultural and rural preferential electricity tariffs for poverty alleviation is not sufficiently controlled. \u25a0 Strong government control over energy service provision and state corporations perpetuates monopolies. \u25a0 National-level institutional arrangements and capacity to develop and implement integrated (beyond sector approach) rural energy development plans are missing. \u25a0 There is no institution with a clear responsibility for providing traditional, non-electric energy services to rural areas or", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4adbe646-4be3-4f6c-9340-ad789e8013b8": {"__data__": {"id_": "4adbe646-4be3-4f6c-9340-ad789e8013b8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e71bf71cbb62ba123ba74f0ce483b2c53da8bcc797ab680565c661eedf860718"}}, "hash": "e71bf71cbb62ba123ba74f0ce483b2c53da8bcc797ab680565c661eedf860718", "text": "for managing and regulating delivery of rural cooking fuel services. BOX 1: KEY INSTITUTIONAL CHALLENGES 7 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam THE CHALLENGES Mismatch between programme framework and existing consumption patterns Not taking into account biomass-based energy consumption in rural areas, the premier rural energy programme is REP. It was launched in 1996 to achieve the national goal of doubling electricity access by 2010. REP and the southern region rural electrification projects have contributed to the delivery of rural electricity services widely, especially in urban areas, through the national power grid. After this project was initiated, education and health care have improved due to the availability of energy services. The availability of motive power for irrigation, industries, handicrafts, agricultural product processing and income-generating opportunities has also increased. REP got assistance from all levels in terms of organizations, finance, planning and resource mobilization and is managed by EVN. Local socio- economic development needs are taken into account because of strict decentralization. However, by limiting the scope at commune centre, rather than reaching out to the households, the impact of REP on poverty is limited because of the fact that it does not maximize the benefit of rural households that have access to electricity. REP does not help the poor directly benefit from policies on preferential electricity pricing, and the gap between the poor and the rich regarding benefits of present rural electricity services remains. To cover remote rural areas, experiments with renewable energy for off-grid electrification involved only pilots for installation of solar, wind and small hydro technologies. The Electricity Law mandates the EVN to develop renewable energy and play the role of a nodal agency while exploiting cross-sectoral synergy in implementation of on- and off-grid rural electrification projects. An off-grid electrification programme, The impact of REP on poverty is limited, because it does not maximize the benefit of rural households that have access to electricity. \u25a0 Policies recognizing high dependence on traditional biomass do not exist. \u25a0 Regulatory framework in rural electricity services delivery to the non-governmental sections (commune electricity boards, electricity contractors, etc.) is not formulated based on laws and transparency. \u25a0 The regulatory framework to enforce compliance with quality standards is inadequate, resulting in poor quality and higher cost of electricity; consequently, affordability and quality of service to end-users in rural areas remain a concern. BOX 2: KEY CHALLENGES IN POLICY AND REGULATORY FRAMEWORK 8 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam THE CHALLENGES generating electricity from diesel and renewable sources, for isolated rural areas was implemented during 1997-2003. Despite the emphasis on rural electricity, biomass (fuelwood and crop residues) from fields, hills and orchards is a major energy source for rural Viet Nam. Most rural households using biomass are self-sufficient in terms of energy. In 1998, more than 92 percent of rural households relied on biomass for cooking and heating (GSO 2000). Since the market for biomass is largely self-regulated, with little government involvement by way of policy, it is termed non-commercial energy. Thus, there is no official data on its production, price or consumption levels. Despite the depletion of forests accelerating, a rural cooking fuel programme to reduce dependence on fuelwood was not officially established and put into prime consideration of the Government in a similar way as the REP. \u25a0 By limiting the reach to the commune centre, rather than to households, REP does not maximize its benefits. \u25a0 With the exception of grid-electricity, programmes to enhance rural access to modern energy have been ineffective because of their pilot status and limited upscaling efforts. \u25a0 There is lack of focus on rural cooking and heating fuels, with no specific programme for reducing dependence, especially that of women, on fuelwood through increased efficiency of stoves and provision of substitute fuels. \u25a0 There is no programme for capacity-building and knowledge sharing on the use of improved stoves and other technologies, such as biomass gasifiers that reduce dependence on biomass. BOX 3: KEY CHALLENGES IN BUILDING AN ENERGY FOR POVERTY REDUCTION PROGRAMME FRAMEWORK Gaps in energy access Subsidies at the national and local levels form the current mechanism for enabling access to rural energy services for poverty reduction and gender equality. Existing subsidy mechanisms for rural energy services through energy pricing for poverty reduction are listed below: \u2022 Subsidy to the lowest tier of electricity consumption corresponding to lower income households \u2022 Subsidy through exemption of freight cost for non-electricity energy services that serve isolated areas \u2022 Subsidy for petroleum products at the national level (decreasing gradually) 9 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam THE CHALLENGES Pricing is a key element in the expansion of electricity", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "71f2503c-95b4-4092-9a27-5e8a505759c6": {"__data__": {"id_": "71f2503c-95b4-4092-9a27-5e8a505759c6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2ed6ddc8e5d326f9e24f50a62886f2a61067d930435a02ee644ee3677c642fb8"}, "3": {"node_id": "07ccd87c-7184-43da-972c-a79dd312a060", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7c6d552888feb3d0b62ed91fa0c8148b6a8406ca8d4f7e24c3cc20694004897e"}}, "hash": "856f0cf5169d5e14c3a9f059d93786293d4b4ebfada2dc874a3f43c2d6d23413", "text": "access to cover the entire country. Viet Nam follows a differential energy pricing policy, focusing on specific groups of users, usage types and geographical areas. The differentiation is between productive and non-productive usages and rural and urban users, with incremental pricing for increasing volumes of consumption. Viet Nam commercially introduced LPG, the cleanest alternative to fuelwood, coal and kerosene, in 1993. By 2000, the average annual demand growth for LPG had increased by almost 50 percent. Domestic consumption of LPG is expected to reach 1.5 million tonnes by 2010 (Thang 2003). Access to LPG cylinders is convenient in major cities, where supply terminals and filling stations are expanding rapidly with door- delivery services. On the other hand, costs of LPG stoves and cylinders limit access in rural areas, slowing the expansion of the supply network. This also brings out a clear relationship between energy consumption and poverty and reinforces the fact that household energy use patterns are income-elastic. The success of REP has improved access to electricity in almost all provinces and regions. Households with access to electricity doubled during 1992-2004, from 48.9 to 90.5 percent, rural households being the major beneficiaries (EVN 2005). However, there is still a gap between urban and rural access to electricity. In 2004, while almost all urban households were grid-connected, only 88 percent of the rural areas were connected. In addition, despite the rapid electrification, consumption levels in the rural areas are still very low. Most of the population that does not have access to electricity resides in remote areas, where grid expansion is expensive and off-grid solutions have not yet made an impact. Additionally, despite government subsidies, electricity prices are still unaffordable for weaker sections of rural communities, leading to low consumption levels in rural households. In 1997, an average lower income household could only afford to pay VND 2,400 (US$ 0.3) per month per head for electricity, while better-off families spent 10 times more (GSO 2000). This disproportionate electricity consumption still continues. The percentage of rural households possessing common electric appliances has not changed much during the period from 1997-2002, and major electricity usage, besides for lighting, is for fans, televisions and radio sets. For example, in 1998, 28.51 percent of rural households had a colour television and in 2002 the figure had increased to 43.61 percent (Table 4). Despite the rapid electrification, consumption levels in the rural areas are still very low. 10 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam THE CHALLENGES TABLE 4 USE OF ELECTRIC APPLIANCES AMONG RURAL HOUSEHOLDS (PERCENTAGE) * Estimated figure Sources GSO (2000) and GSO (2004) \u25a0 Despite improved access, the price of modern energy alternatives (e.g. LPG for cooking) is too high and unaffordable for lower income households. \u25a0 Government subsidies have enabled increased access to electricity, but the price is still too high for the poor. \u25a0 Off-grid solutions have not yet resulted in significant improvement in access to energy services. \u25a0 Non-state electricity providers at the commune level are constrained by limited capacities and poor access to technology. BOX 4: KEY CHALLENGES IN WIDENING ACCESS TO ENERGY SERVICES The closest point to the commune that the national grid can reach is the transforming station located at the rural commune. Since EVN does not reach the household levels in rural areas, investment from others is required. Therefore, rural electricity distributors and investors are allowed to operate at the commune level; however, they have insufficient technical and financial capacities to invest and manage the commune grid properly. The per-kWh price of electricity in rural areas is often higher than in urban areas due to transmission losses and high management costs. Technology efficiency and fuel option concerns Viet Nam has formulated policies and programmes for energy efficiency and conservation, under which efficient use of fuel is promoted through improved technology in transmission, end-use appliances and equipment, and through increased use of renewable energy.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "07ccd87c-7184-43da-972c-a79dd312a060": {"__data__": {"id_": "07ccd87c-7184-43da-972c-a79dd312a060", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2ed6ddc8e5d326f9e24f50a62886f2a61067d930435a02ee644ee3677c642fb8"}, "2": {"node_id": "71f2503c-95b4-4092-9a27-5e8a505759c6", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "856f0cf5169d5e14c3a9f059d93786293d4b4ebfada2dc874a3f43c2d6d23413"}}, "hash": "7c6d552888feb3d0b62ed91fa0c8148b6a8406ca8d4f7e24c3cc20694004897e", "text": "Domestic and commercial consumption are both addressed in the policies and Electric appliances 1997/1998 2001/2002 per household Total Rural 