 international donors. \u25a0 Clean coal technologies are not applied in the production and processing of coal for end use. \u25a0 High cost of power-saving lamps prevents usage in lower income households. BOX 5: KEY TECHNOLOGICAL CHALLENGES 12 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam THE CHALLENGES 2 http://www.sme.com.vn/Article.aspx?TopicID=107. 3 Internal UNDP-GEF document; Project Implementation Review of 2007. electricity market, allowing almost all types of entities with appropriate capacity to participate in the provision of electricity services. Despite this effort, market penetration by private investors remains at a modest level due to low capacity and lack of incentives for investment. Industrial SMEs create important employment opportunities. In 2002, SMEs in Viet Nam employed 26 percent of the workforce, contributing to 25 percent of the GDP. In addition, energy demand is expected to grow fast in the coming years, given the rapid growth in the number of SMEs and micro enterprises during 2002-20052. Viet Nam had an estimated energy consumption of 2.4 million tonnes of oil equivalent (Mtoe) in 2005, a figure projected to reach 4.5 Mtoe by 2010 (UNDP 2005). SMEs often disregard energy efficiency of technologies and equipment and selection of appropriate fuels, because other issues are considered more important. Management capacity and knowledge on energy-efficient technologies are poor in SMEs, which often use second-hand, obsolete equipment. Such equipment has low energy end-use efficiency and consumes large amounts of energy, leading to low efficiency of energy services, low quality of products, high costs of production and difficulty in competing with large industries. Part of the problem also includes a serious lack of capital to invest in modern technologies. Most commercial banks do not lend to SMEs for energy-saving purposes as the latter cannot meet their conditions for loans. SMEs also struggle to grow because, generally, they are not provided with training courses and materials, forums for information exchange on technologies and equipment with high energy efficiency, awareness-raising activities and management skills for energy-based businesses. The UNDP-GEF Operational Programme 5 project, initiated in 2005, for the Promotion of Energy Conservation in Small-to-Medium scale Enterprises (PECSME) focuses on removal of barriers (financial, institutional, information, market, policy/regulatory, technical) in the widespread application of energy conservation and energy efficiency in SMEs in Viet Nam (UNDP 2005). The implementation of the project started in 2006 and the key SME sectors addressed in the project are brick making, ceramics, textiles, paper and food processing. To date3, PECSME demonstration activities have achieved a total annual energy savings of 515 tonnes of oil equivalent (toe), and the projects implemented by PECSME partners have realized annual energy savings of 1,291 toe.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7bf632a2-11df-4e5c-a822-285fdf967047": {"__data__": {"id_": "7bf632a2-11df-4e5c-a822-285fdf967047", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3f19ed90f2dd59f173c596e44f83a1d7dc300be0f7efdb4881642ef7428307d9"}, "2": {"node_id": "5e7afe90-0086-440a-9613-ac89f32f4fef", "n