7eeac1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c216caee58725a91c32ed09941605f4d3843eeb43fa43eb79190075e5929b5cf"}}, "hash": "6af59c804792675281a8501e7986d8c89e9e91d9e7fb427ad8a971603e1094f5", "text": "investments from SMEs that are worth US$ 751,000. Limited access to finance Financial mechanisms to improve distribution of energy services through non-state energy service providers at the national, regional and local levels include tapping private investment, including for rural electrification, biogas digesters and small hydropower, and loans to SMEs for energy saving and energy efficiency from so called techno-commercial banks at preferential interest rates. The financial mechanisms to improve energy access by lower income households include: (1) the Social Policy Bank that has a micro-lending programme without collateral; (2) the People\u2019s Credit Funds (PCFs) that function as microcredit cooperatives; and (3) grass-roots organizations such as the Viet Nam Women\u2019s Union and Viet Nam Farmers\u2019 Union. The PCFs are established to promote income-generating activities for lower income households lacking capital and assets for mortgage. The main objective of the funds is to avoid heavy interest rates in rural areas. Lower income households can use loans from these funds to access rural energy services. \u25a0 SMEs, in general, and those associated with energy entrepreneurship, in particular, find it difficult to access loans from banks due to stringent loan conditions. \u25a0 There is no concerted effort to integrate knowledge, skills and technology for energy-efficient enterprise development. \u25a0 There is no structured training and development programme for energy entrepreneurs. \u25a0 There is no documentation and dissemination of best practices in energy efficiency for SMEs. \u25a0 Biogas and biomass technologies have not been promoted as business opportunities. BOX 6: KEY CHALLENGES TO ENERGY ENTREPRENEURSHIP 14 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam THE CHALLENGES \u25a0 The loan conditions set for projects related to energy conservation and energy efficiency from techno-commercial banks are still too stringent, so SMEs, cooperatives and rural households (especially lower income households) cannot access loans for investment in energy-efficient technologies and equipment. \u25a0 The terms and regulations for loans in microcredit programmes limit the sanctioned loan amounts. \u25a0 There is lack of documentation of experiences and impacts of finance models for poverty reduction, including that of the development of rural energy services delivery. BOX 7: KEY CHALLENGES TO FACILITATING ACCESS TO FINANCE \u25a0 There is a lack of focus on documenting and replicating successful energy-related initiatives for women. \u25a0 There is a lack of focus on gender-related monitoring and evaluation (M&E). BOX 8: KEY CHALLENGES TO GENDER MAINSTREAMING WITH REGARDS TO ENERGY Gender concerns Biomass continues to be a major source of energy for cooking and heating for the majority of rural households in Viet Nam. The dominance of biomass in the energy mix creates drudgery for rural women, as they are the primary collectors of biomass. Although many women are involved in economic activities, their participation in energy-based income-generating activities could be much enhanced through improving their access to modern energy services. This is true especially in the context of agricultural production and associated activities such as small-scale food processing and handicrafts. Gaps in access to information There are few modalities for knowledge and information sharing in rural energy planning. Most of the training, information dissemination and sharing of best practices, such as that which concerns improved cook stoves and biogas production, are conducted and documented at the project level and at specific locations. Dissemination of the existing information is done in an ad hoc manner. There is no formal system for The dominance of biomass in the energy mix creates drudgery for rural women, as they are the primary collectors of biomass. 15 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam THE CHALLENGES collating and recording experiences that could enable information sharing among the stakeholders concerned with rural energy. Currently, national- and local-level capacities to collect, collate, analyse, manage and disseminate rural energy service delivery information is limited. \u25a0 Documentation of rural energy information and activities is done only at the project level. \u25a0 Information is not disseminated and collected into a formal system. \u25a0 Lack of capacities in all levels limits access to information. BOX 9: KEY CHALLENGES TO ESTABLISHING AN INFORMATION SYSTEM \u25a0 Key indicators and benchmarks for M&E of energy and poverty related concerns are not part of the planning and implementation of current rural energy projects and programmes. \u25a0 National- and local-level institutions cannot set indicators and benchmarks related to energy and poverty issues because of inadequate capacities.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d3db4a7d-ec44-4e77-b68f-197d7c7eeac1": {"__data__": {"id_": "d3db4a7d-ec44-4e77-b68f-197d7c7eeac1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": 