duction. Meanwhile, the provincial departments that are responsible for energy development, along with local governments, should also be involved in poverty reduction programmes and projects. Lack of institutional focus on rural energy provision for poverty alleviation and decentralization can be further addressed by developing capacity to use tools and frameworks to be used towards planning integrated rural energy development, while also taking into account poverty reduction initiatives of MARD and MoLISA and its associated bodies. The tools and frameworks for integrated rural energy planning could be used beyond the energy sub-sectors (coal, electricity, oil and gas), which could enhance the cross-sectoral cooperation for implementation of rural energy plans for poverty alleviation. Seeking cross-sectoral synergy could also help reduce dependence on biomass energy for cooking and disseminate widely technological solutions (e.g. improved cook stoves) for increasing efficiency of cooking fuel use and minimizing self-supply of such rural traditional energy types. MARD could manage the rural cooking fuel programme and act as the nodal professional agency. It could also facilitate cross-sectoral cooperation between MoI, Viet Nam Women\u2019s Union (VWU) and other institutions and organizations for the execution of biofuel surveys, distribution of improved cook stoves and selection of rural cooking fuels suitable for each region and sub-region. Also, international agencies should mainstream energy provision into all appropriate rural development and poverty reduction projects and interventions they support. Seeking cross- sectoral synergy could also help reduce dependence on biomass energy for cooking and disseminate widely technological solutions. 17 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam MEETING THE CHALLENGES Enabling policy and regulatory framework Biomass accounts for a significant share of the total energy consumption of Viet Nam. Thus, national energy policies must take into account traditional sources of energy, afforestation programmes and other mechanisms to increase proliferation of energy-efficient biomass and ensure long-term sustainability of traditional rural energy sources. Policies to support energy programmes concerning traditional energy use are necessary and must be integrated into development plans at the national, provincial and district levels, with specific targets and time frames and regular monitoring and feedback. In terms of regulatory issues, lower income households within a community need to be provided with \u2018enablers\u2019 of electricity and modern energy sources, such as differential energy price, subsidies in supplies and end-use spares, and an increase in off-grid electricity provision. The regulatory framework to enforce compliance with quality standards needs to be strengthened, and guidelines for commune grid development that benefit end-users in rural areas must be included. Energy programme framework for encouraging poverty reduction A balanced programme framework for energy services with the aim to reduce poverty consists of, among others, a grid-connected rural electrification programme; a renewable energy development programme, especially serving off-grid rural electrification in remote, mountainous areas that are not reached by the national power grid; and a rural cooking fuel programme. The programme framework also needs to recognize the existing consumption patterns. To address poverty concerns, there must be a clear focus on addressing the inefficient utilization of biomass energy. Development of afforestation programmes and other mechanisms that aim to increase proliferation of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7dee05df-171d-4b45-b809-c60032eb7bdd": {"__data__": {"id_": "7dee05df-171d-4b45-b809-c60032eb7bdd", "embedding": null, "metadata": {