ific targets and implementation steps. Energy services delivery should be followed up to the household level, ensuring that the poor also benefit directly, and if they do not, the gaps need to be assessed and addressed. Programmes targeting improved rural energy access focusing on wide range of energy types should be established in order to accelerate the accomplishment of these goals. For example, off-grid electricity programme could be continued and scaled-up. Promoting access to energy for poverty reduction An emphasis on making energy services affordable for and available to the poor is necessary in order to alleviate poverty. The deprivation of electricity in remote areas is one of the major impediments to the socio- economic development of rural communities. In this context, EVN is the key agency set to solve the problems of electricity services delivery to rural and remote areas. EVN\u2019s subsidiaries, local electricity companies and other electricity providers in rural areas can facilitate electricity provision to lower income households through a series of measures that must include enforcement of guidelines for commune grid development. EVN\u2019s and other electricity providers\u2019 capacities in this area need strengthening. After guidelines for electricity service provision are followed, further efforts to mainstream the poverty considerations into energy service provision are needed. For example, this process could occur through the transformation of commune electricity boards or cooperatives into rural energy enterprises. A system to evaluate the impacts of different energy service delivery models in addressing development needs for poverty reduction also needs to be in place. Commune-based and enterprise- oriented electricity provision can be taken forward by setting aside resources for building capacity for non-EVN electricity providers as a way to improve their performance. The communes can be further supported through a scheme of low-interest finance to rejuvenate and increase the capacity of commune electrification. Since energy provision for remote rural areas may not be viable through the centralized grid, lower income households are largely dependent on non-state rural energy service providers. A programme on Programmes targeting improved rural energy access focusing on wide range of energy types should be established. 19 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam MEETING THE CHALLENGES rural energy services should be established to focus on aspects related to the quality and affordability of all different forms of energy services. This can be facilitated through official development assistance (ODA) support that focuses on these aspects of energy services. An agreement among MoI, MARD and other agencies and international donors can be made to provide guidance tools for mobilizing resources for further development of affordable and quality energy services through decentralized service providers. Local provincial departments and PETROLIMEX networks should be mandated to provide non-electricity energy services to lower income households. To encourage the switchover from traditional to modern energy, mechanisms to encourage use of electricity, coal-based energy and LPG in remote areas should be established. Demonstration schemes for clean coal processing and LPG could inspire such a switch from traditional biomass to cleaner fuels. Off-grid renewable energy technologies (RETs) could also be part of the solution, especially in places where the use of renewable energy is more viable than grid extension. To make progress on this front, some government intervention is likely necessary. The rural communities should be informed about the potential benefits of off-grid RETs, as well as the realities resulting from the infeasibility of grid extension to remote areas. The latter is very important, because high expectations of grid electricity may prevent adoption of RETs. Awareness of renewable energies can be promoted through information", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8ac6a684-bdd8-4a9d-ab60-9ce557b4b25e": {"__data__": {"id_": "8ac6a684-bdd8-4a9d-ab60-9ce557b4b25e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c465f6d6a9f0fc6178a695c01c38e7485cc16df6c4a2caa23944f053b9eab0f0"}}, "hash": "c465f6d6a9f0fc6178a695c01c38e7485cc16df6c4a2caa23944f053b9eab0f0", "text": "programmes to both developers and consumers. Both groups need tools to evaluate the technologies and benefit from demonstrations which provide sufficient information on operation and maintenance (Nguyen 2007). As yet another consideration, to increase the level of energy consumption for productive purposes in micro business and SMEs, off-grid renewable energy programmes should be accelerated and decentralized to Provincial People\u2019s Committees so that development is more demand-driven. As with other types of energy services, renewable energy potential requires a thorough assessment of quality and affordability. To enhance the affordable dissemination of RETs at the household level, a number of initiatives could be implemented; for example, a targeted subsidy or consumer credit system could be established for those segments of consumers who need it the most. Consumer credit will provide financial assistance that comes from a financial institute or a local bank, which spreads the investment cost over some years. Usually, an overseeing body is needed for local banks to approve assistance. A more attractive system to rural households, however, could be the establishment of an energy service company (ESCO), which could act as a non-ENV electricity The rural communities should be informed about the potential benefits of off-grid RETs. 20 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam MEETING THE CHALLENGES provider, using RETs to electrify the rural areas. An ESCO would buy RET systems in bulk and install them for users, who would pay for the energy services, not for the hardware. This way, the investments and costs are spread out over a long period of time. Promoting energy efficiency and opportunities for entrepreneurship Poverty reduction efforts demand that energy service provision be affordable to lower income households and viable to enterprises providing or consuming energy. Hence, the efficiency of energy supply systems becomes a crucial factor, because it impacts both affordability to consumers and viability to entrepreneurs. This can be supported further by, for example, a fresh marketing strategy to change consumer behaviour by aggressive dissemination of power-saving bulbs, targeting households in both urban and rural areas. Energy-efficient light bulbs will be a more cost-efficient choice than traditional bulbs in the longer term; however, increasing awareness of these options may also be necessary. For non-electricity-based energy consumption, a survey of consumer preferences needs to be conducted to support development of efficient, user-friendly biomass technologies, such as improved cook stoves and kilns. MARD can conduct periodic pre-harvest surveys, make inventories and develop efficiency studies regarding biomass use for energy, and then use the results to provide practical steps to improve availability and efficiency of use. To enhance the viability of energy-based SMEs, it is necessary to increase also their awareness of efficient energy technologies and fuels and to build their capacities to access bank loans for financing technology improvement or fuel change. Information about opportunities in energy service provision should be documented and disseminated to SMEs, banks and support agencies as it is to entrepreneurs and consumers in order to facilitate rational choices of technology and energy options. For example, accurate and reliable information about energy-saving projects should be accessible to SMEs, creditors and lending agencies. Also, results from state and academic research and development projects on energy solutions should be made more accessible to SMEs, even as databases of best practices in energy efficiency are established and disseminated. Making finance more accessible Energy service projects for enhancing rural development should be considered eligible for loans. Lower income households in remote areas 21 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam MEETING THE CHALLENGES need financial support as do entrepreneurs associated with energy service delivery in such areas. For effective results, financial instruments such as soft loans and subsidies for energy service delivery need to be extended in a manner that supports enterprise and competitiveness. Hence, open bidding needs to be applied for subsidy provision so that private and non-state enterprises can participate. Enabling mechanisms that simplify access to finance for small and medium energy providers and energy- based enterprises can support the open bidding process. Banks should share risks with energy service providers and invest in energy projects for SMEs. The Social Policy Bank should also cover rural energy development, particularly for household usages. Since development of energy-based enterprises is crucial for poverty reduction, Viet Nam Techno-Commercial Bank\u2019s loan programme that encourages SMEs to achieve energy efficiency must be strengthened. Also, the current rules on lending need to be revised so that SMEs take up energy conservation and efficiency initiatives. The micro-loan programme for agriculture and rural development for lower income households that aims to create income- generating opportunities can incorporate energy concerns, and access to the programme should be expanded.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7be9677c-503c-4c93-a9c4-421577646970": {"__data__": {"id_": "7be9677c-503c-4c93-a9c4-421577646970", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5cb249b0e0e133106818d8bdd4e3878d538d85e748f4d4d3dbf907a1a680644e"}}, "hash": "5cb249b0e0e133106818d8bdd4e3878d538d85e748f4d4d3dbf907a1a680644e", "text": "Simultaneously, terms and regulations for microfinance should be modified to enable small rural players to access finance. Donor agencies working closely with the Government can facilitate the involvement of energy auditors, energy consultants, energy service companies and engineering firms, mainly in technical aspects, to appraise energy conservation projects, as it would help build confidence in bankers towards energy-related projects. At the local level, provinces should determine the need for electricity among lower income households and develop their own networks to cater to such needs. The provinces, along with EVN, should be mandated to mobilize resources for upgrading commune grids. Finally, an assessment system to evaluate the impacts of finance models for poverty reduction, including the development of rural energy services delivery, needs to be in place in order to keep track of and learn from new programmes and progress. Mainstreaming gender into energy and poverty initiatives There is little documented information on energy-related gender concerns in Viet Nam. However, issues related to women\u2019s drudgery are well-documented at the international level. Experiences worldwide and some successful initiatives in Viet Nam show that this issue can be best addressed through the provision of efficient energy services for cooking, For effective results, financial instruments for energy service delivery need to be extended in a manner that supports enterprise and competitiveness. 22 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam MEETING THE CHALLENGES wherein credit-based initiatives for large-scale dissemination of biogas need to be expanded. The efforts need to be complemented by assessing and documenting the ways in which other decentralized power generation technologies, such as small and pico hydro initiatives, have benefited women. Another key issue related to mainstreaming gender into energy and poverty initiatives is the development of gender-related benchmarks and indicators that measure the benefits that arise from energy services, in general, and rural energy service, in particular. In the case of the latter, indicators should take into account gaps between higher and lower income groups, urban and rural users, and women and men (UNDP 2007a). Making information available All forms of documentation, including surveys conducted, concerning specific energy-related projects should focus on questions relating to energy and poverty concerns and related best practices. A database of this information, as well as that concerning rural energy and development needs, in general, must be established. This information system should encompass technology developers, financiers, businesses and their services, energy service providers and low-cost technologies. Building capacity for existing staff working in this field (from national to local levels) to collect, treat, manage and disseminate information is important as well. Better methods for monitoring and evaluation Key indicators and benchmarks for M&E of energy and poverty concerns are not part of the planning and implementation of current rural energy projects and programmes, but the development of such tools would be beneficial. Indicators and benchmarks that measure benefits from energy services, in general, and rural energy services, in particular, and, more importantly, that keep track of those who benefit, can be developed and put into the statistical yearbook. Some of the key objectives in developing a comprehensive M&E framework for addressing energy and poverty concerns in tandem are indicated below: \u2022 Sectoral indicators and benchmarks should be developed for coal, petroleum and electricity \u2022 Rural energy surveys should be conducted periodically, utilizing indicators that measure factors in terms of per geographical unit or per capita, such as levels of household consumption, productive consumption, energy based enterprises and energy provision networks Indicators should take into account gaps between higher and lower income groups, urban and rural users, and women and men. 23 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam MEETING THE CHALLENGES I CONCLUSION \u2022 Information should be collected from rural development projects, sectors and national programmes/projects \u2022 The periodic VHLSS should include an additional section on linkages between income and energy use and should collect consistent energy data at the household level Technical guidelines and management procedures must be formulated and enforced by local authorities. Requirements and contents of capacity- building for statistical information staff need to be developed so that they can successfully and effectively set indicators and benchmarks related to the specific issues. Then, capacity-building for staff members who are working in energy, economic and statistical information sectors should be conducted so that they have sufficient knowledge and skills in gathering, managing, treating and storing data related to energy- and poverty-related issues. t is apparent that sustainable energy development is a prerequisite to pursuing rapid sustainable economic growth that reduces poverty while ensuring a comprehensive, pro-poor growth strategy. Challenges and gaps in energy development for poverty reduction in Viet Nam are found to have", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "02696913-4c55-460e-8c98-9bf190cec317": {"__data__": {"id_": "02696913-4c55-460e-8c98-9bf190cec317", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7c811c110444b76650c406848dce71416a9e99cb63f5d2f7113647cc8f5d1939"}}, "hash": "7c811c110444b76650c406848dce71416a9e99cb63f5d2f7113647cc8f5d1939", "text": "policy, institutional and technology aspects. In particular, although rural poverty reduction and energy services should go hand- in-hand, the required cross-sectoral institutional synergy is lacking at the central and provincial levels. Patterns in energy development focus also contribute to the current inefficiency. Large investment in rural electrification, while resulting in better access for the poor to energy, might compromise investment in and drive away the focus on other types of energy, particularly, the renewable sources that the poor depend on heavily. Also, various existing financial schemes for SME development, rural development and poverty reduction do not address modern energy services at all. The resulting lack of information on the roles of energy services to inform policy and programme development is considerably responsible for the current situation. To fill these gaps, a concerted effort for policy and institutional development and financial resource mobilization should be in place, involving multi-stakeholders, including government agencies, research institutions and academics, local authorities, and civil society. Apart from issues concerning information gaps and lack of resources, biomass potential is a very important factor surrounding the future of energy and poverty in Viet Nam. Despite the fact that biomass accounts for a significant share of the national energy consumption, and is the 24 Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam CONCLUSION almost exclusive source of energy for the poor, it is ignored by the Government at the policy level. Efficient usage of biomass is a key area that could provide opportunities to ensure sustainability, quality and affordability of energy service for the poor. It, however, requires greater recognition in national energy policy and appropriate follow-through and allocation of financial resources. At the immediate stage, investment in R&D for low-cost technology (such as improved cook stoves and kilns) could meet the need for cleaner and more efficient biomass usage. Concerning financial aspects, existing microcredit schemes could certainly provide support for rural energy development with slight adjustment to the considerations and regulations for lending. Regarding information and knowledge sharing, poverty-energy linkage indicators can be included in the existing poverty assessment and household living standard surveys. In the long term, modern renewable energy offers great potential for providing energy services to the rural poor, especially those not connected to electricity grids. At specific locations and petroleum product price levels, they are likely to be cheaper than fossil fuel alternatives, which also impose external costs on the environment and human health. Internalizing these costs will improve the competitiveness of renewable energy vis \u00e0 vis the non-renewable fossil fuel sources. Besides improved living conditions, RETs also offer opportunities for income generation (UNDP 2007b). To facilitate comprehensive energy policy development, a nation-wide survey to inventorize biomass and other renewable energy sources and technology capability should be undertaken on a regular basis. Decentralization in the energy sector should be fostered to give more autonomy and responsibility to local authorities in dealing with local energy needs for local development. 26 SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES No institution with clear mandate and responsibility for providing traditional/ non-electric energy services to rural areas or for managing and regulating rural cooking fuel services delivery Lack of institutional focus on rural energy provision for poverty alleviation and decentralization Strong government control over energy service provision, and state corporations remain close to monopolies Institutional Structure Policy and Regulatory Framework High dependence on traditional biomass energy not recognized in policy framework Inadequate mechanism to provide sufficient energy services to lower income households in rural areas; Existing tariff framework, despite government subsidy, remains problematic Clearly define responsibilities and roles so that implementation of institutional reforms can be sped up Corporate entities should be given a greater role and cover remote areas and deprived communities A memorandum of understanding between corporate entities and government ministries should be prepared, setting out terms of delivery and pricing for the benefit of lower income households Set up a short-term cross- sectoral committee to ensure that the division of roles and responsibilities becomes a reality and is directed towards greater institutional decentralization for developing rural energy services for poverty reduction Provincial departments responsible for energy development as well as local governments should be involved in poverty reduction programmes and projects Develop capacity to use tools and frameworks for integrated rural energy development planning as they relate to poverty reduction initiatives in MARD and MoLISA and its associated bodies; Build this capacity across all sectors, improving cross-sectoral cooperation Seek cross-sectoral synergy to help reduce dependence on biomass energy for cooking; Disseminate technological solutions (e.g. improved cook stoves) for increasing efficiency of cooking fuel use and minimizing self-supply", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0eb3d72d-bc1e-4005-b2c9-5b85f8b74180": {"__data__": {"id_": "0eb3d72d-bc1e-4005-b2c9-5b85f8b74180", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy and Poverty in Viet Nam", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-and-poverty-viet-nam", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "211715ca9123ea71b7c7f44e0f95dd2187c75dabad459f47c1321585a3baf8b8"}}, "hash": "211715ca9123ea71b7c7f44e0f95dd2187c75dabad459f47c1321585a3baf8b8", "text": "of such rural traditional energy types MARD could manage the rural cooking fuel programme and act as the nodal professional agency MARD could facilitate cross-sectoral cooperation between MoI, VWU and other agencies for biofuel surveys, distribution of improved cook stoves and selection of rural cooking fuels suitable for each region and sub-region National energy policies must take into account the inefficiency of traditional sources of energy Policies that support energy programmes concerning traditional energy use and enhance efficient biomass use are necessary Programmes concerning traditional energy use need to be integrated into development plans at the national, provincial and district levels, with specific targets and time frames and regular monitoring and feedback Lower income households within the community need to be provided with \u2018enablers\u2019 of electricity and modern energy sources, such as differential energy price and subsidies that favour lower income households in both supplies and end-use spares, along with an increase in off-grid electricity provision The regulatory framework to enforce compliance with quality standards must include guidelines for commune grid development that benefit end-users in rural areas 27 By limiting the reach to the commune centre, rather than to households, the Rural Electrification Programme does not maximize its benefits; gap between rural and urban electricity access still exists With the exception of those concerning electricity, programmes to enhance rural access to modern energy have been ineffective, because they have been implemented largely on a pilot basis with limited efforts to upscale Mismatch between programme framework and existing consumption patterns Programme Concerns THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES Develop a balanced programme framework that recognizes existing consumption patterns To address poverty concerns, the programme framework focus needs to be on addressing the inefficient utilization of biomass energy Afforestation programmes and other mechanisms to increase proliferation of energy-efficient biomass and ensure long-term sustainability of traditional rural energy sources need to be developed Basic rural energy programmes should be given more emphasis at the national level, and not only characterized as research programmes Government needs to develop a master plan with specific targets and implementation steps Programmes need to include a research component Extend energy services delivery to the household level, ensuring that the poor benefit directly, and if they don\u2019t, the gaps need to be assessed and addressed Programmes targeting improved rural energy access focusing on a wide range of energy types should be established 28 SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES (CONTINUED...) THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES Limited reach by ENV to rural and remote areas impedes socio-economic development of remote rural communities and prevents adequate dissemination of affordable modern energy services to the poor Since energy provision to remote rural areas may not be viable through the centralized grid, lower income households are largely dependent on non-state rural energy service providers There is limited awareness of off-grid renewable energy technologies as a part of the solution where grid extension is not viable Access Issues Documentation of rural energy information and activities is done only at the project level and is not disseminated and collected into a formal system, partly due to lack of capacities in all levels The EVN\u2019s subsidiaries, local electricity companies, and other electricity providers in rural areas can facilitate electricity provision to lower income households through a series of measures that must include enforcement of guidelines for commune grid development Capacities of EVN and other electricity providers need strengthening, especially regarding the enforcement of guidelines in commune grid development Mainstream poverty considerations into energy service provision through transforming commune electricity boards or cooperatives into rural energy enterprises Establish a programme on rural energy services to focus on factors related to quality and affordability; this can be facilitated through official development assistance (ODA) support An agreement among MoI, MARD, and other agencies and international donors can be made to provide guidance tools for mobilizing resources for further development of affordable and quality energy services through decentralized service providers Local provincial departments and PETROLIMEX networks should be mandated to provide non- electricity energy services to lower income households Awareness of the benefits of off-grid renewable energy technologies as well as the realities resulting from the infeasibility of grid extension to remote areas should be communicated to rural communities Assess the possible mechanisms to disseminate RETs at household level and develop information programmes for developers and consumers Documentation and surveys conducted as part of specific projects should also focus on questions related to energy and poverty concerns and the best practices in this area Establish a database concerning information on rural energy and development needs as well as best practices Building capacity for existing", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1