cluding that which regards development of rural energy service delivery Financing Concerns Increase SME\u2019s awareness of efficient energy technologies and fuels and build their capacities to access bank loans for financing technology improvement or fuel change Information about energy service provision should be documented and disseminated to SMEs, banks and support agencies in order to facilitate rational choices of technology and energy options Accurate and reliable information about energy-saving projects should be accessible to SMEs, creditors and lending agencies, including results from state and academic R&D projects on energy solutions, even as databases of best practices in energy efficiency are established and disseminated Viet Nam Techno-Commercial Bank\u2019s loan programme for SMEs to achieve energy saving and energy efficiency must be strengthened Current rules on lending need to be revised so that SMEs take up energy conservation and efficiency initiatives Micro-loan programme for agriculture and rural development for lower income households to create income- generating opportunities can incorporate energy concerns and access to the programme can be expanded Terms and regulations for microfinancing should be modified so that small rural players can access finance An assessment system to evaluate the impacts of finance models for poverty reduction, including development of rural energy service delivery, needs to be in place 30 SCHEMATIC REPRESENTATION OF CHALLENGES AND MODALITIES TO MEET THE CHALLENGES (CONTINUED...) THE CHALLENGES MEETING THE CHALLENGES Lack of focus on successful energy-related initiatives for women Lack of focus on gender-related M&E Gender Concerns Key indicators and benchmarks for monitoring energy and poverty concerns are not part of the planning and implementation of current rural energy projects and programmes Limited M&E framework There is inadequate capacity at the national and local level to set indicators and benchmarks r