ion . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 57 Annex 2 Sample calculations for electricity production (contd.). . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 58 Annex 3 Sample calculations for energy end-uses . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 59 Annex 4.1 Sample calculations for baseline scenario (2006): Cooking and heating. . . . . . . . . 60 Annex 4.2 Sample calculations for baseline scenario (2006): Lighting and other end-use services. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 61 Annex 4.3 Sample calculations for baseline scenario (2006): Liquid fuel based end-use services. . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 62 Annex 5.1 Sample calculations for 2010: Cooking and heating . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 63 Annex 5.2 Sample calculations for 2010: Lighting and other end-use services. . . . . . . . . . . . 64 Annex 5.3 Sample calculations for 2010: Liquid fuel based end-use services. . . . . . . . . . . . . 65 About the authors . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . 66 Foreword v Foreword AT ThE 2005 WoRlD SUMMIT, world leaders reiterated their pledge to the Millennium Develop- ment Goals (MDGs) by committing to support the development and implementation of MDG-based national development strategies. In response, the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) embarked on an ambitious plan to support countries in preparing long term, results-based devel- opment strategies in line with the MDGs. At the heart of the plan is an integrated package of policy advice and technical support, known as \u2018MDG Support Services\u2019, aimed at strengthening countries\u2019 capacity to achieve the MDGs. UNDP started rolling out MDG Support Services initially in 19 countries in 2006 with the target of reaching a total of 120 countries by 2008. Access to energy is central to all aspects of sustainable development, including access to water, agricul- tural and industrial productivity, health care, educational attainment, job creation and climate change impacts. Nearly two thirds of the world\u2019s poor have no access or limited access to this very basic ener- gy input. Affordable, accessible and reliable energy supply is critical for the lives of poor people as well as for the economic growth of a country. Therefore, this Guide emphasizes the need for an inte- grated, multisectoral approach to energy needs assessments and cost estimates. Although access to clean energy facilitates economic development and sustainable livelihoods by improving quality of life for the poor, it is not often that planners of developing countries consider energy delivery as an integrating instrument that supports a comprehensive national development path. Developing coun- try governments can play a major role in addressing poverty by ensuring access to energy services through both centralized and decentralized energy sources. In the recent past, there has been an excessive focus on the provision of electricity to poor people, which is not always the most appropri- ate, cost effective and efficient way of providing energy services to the poor. Thanks to the UN Millennium Project, a number of tools already exist for assisting governments in esti- mating costs for interrelated actions needed to achieve the MDGs. Recognizing the critical role that energy plays in reaching the MDGs, the UNDP Regional Centre for Asia and the Pacific in Bangkok built upon an earlier version of the UN Millennium Project\u2019s energy costing", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6decc24f-de35-4f78-95dc-71cecdca7c49": {"__data__": {"id_": "6decc24f-de35-4f78-95dc-71cecdca7c49", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy Costing Tool: User Guide", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4d66addb04eb5e2193e25d9ece3831c7951c2ad560e6b9204e42b5b85ae06c81"}, "3": {"node_id": "392edb2d-de63-4c34-ad02-ea212ba83292", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e3d2c284cf4afb8f60619fca44d682cb5257f10e417da575c55299425b37b6b8"}}, "hash": "e70723d896849f87229a6db2bdf321196e945614267e8712972629f2ebe5699f", "text": "tool that was first applied in Senegal, and redesigned it for the context of Asia and the Pacific. This Tool is designed for use by government planners and decision makers as they adapt their national development strategies to meet country-specific targets for the year 2015 based on the MDGs. A cru- cial part of this process is MDG costing, which quantifies the specific financial and human resources needed, as well as infrastructure required, to meet the MDGs. Costing is part of a larger needs assess- ment process in which countries define specific interventions and outcome targets consistent with the MDGs. Pilot runs of the tool make a convincing case for the opportunities it provides for integrat- ed resource planning in support of MDGs. Marcia VJ Kran Head of Policy and Programmes, UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok January 2009 vi Energy costing tool user\u2019s guide Preface ThE PREPARATIoN of national development strategies based on the Millennium Development Goals (MDG) provides a unique opportunity to integrate energy access considerations as a vital element of economic development, along side reducing hunger and improving health care and edu- cation. The need for a multisectoral approach to energy needs assessment and systematic costing of the available options can hardly be over emphasized. The Energy Costing Tool and the User\u2019s Guide are the product of almost two years of effort, extensive consultation and trial runs amongst partner countries in the Asia-Pacific region. The Energy Costing Tool lays out an exhaustive menu of energy technology options and their costs for a country in the context of it\u2019s own socio-economic, geographic and resources baseline. Focus is on modern energy carriers, as well as quality of energy end use services and not the quantum of energy derived. It helps identify likely minimum cost energy mixes, for the short, medium and the long term, especially by aligning energy access investments in the national budget. The User's Guide is organized into three sections. The first provides a brief introduction to the context in which the Tool was developed. It also outlines the national decision-making process that must under- pin an energy costing exercise. This process entails identifying MDG-compatible energy interventions and setting long-term energy access targets. The second section provides a detailed introduction to the Energy Costing Tool itself, including step-by-step instructions on using the Tool. The last part is an annex where descriptions of the calculations performed by the Tool are presented. Sections 1 and 2, and subsections 4.9 to 11 of this Guide have been developed based on the content of an earlier version of the Guide developed by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) and the UN Millennium Project. The Tool is Excel-based, which enables transparencies in terms of inputs, methods, relationships, equa- tions and outputs. It is also flexible enough for the user to intervene at every stage of its use. The Tool has 13 worksheets in total, beginning with the \u2018Cover\u2019 and ending with the \u2018Summary\u2019. The summary worksheet reports the results in tables and figures. Out of the remaining 11 modules (or worksheets), there are one each for \u2018Overview\u2019 and \u2018Glossary of technologies\u2019, two are exclusively for data entry (\u2018Design parameters\u2019 and \u2018MDG needs\u2019), three modules are for unit energy cost estimation (\u2018Energy production\u2019, \u2018Electricity production\u2019 and \u2018Energy end-use\u2019), one module for costing (\u2018Capacity devel- opment\u2019) and three modules for MDG scenarios (\u2018Baseline\u2019, \u2018Short-term\u2019 and \u2018Medium-term\u2019 scenarios). Nandita Mongia Regional Programme Coordinator and Team Leader Regional Energy Programme for Poverty Reduction (REP-PoR) UNDP Regional Centre in Bangkok Acknowledgements vii Acknowledgements ThE DEVEloPMENT oF ThE Tool received support and encouragement from a large number of colleagues within UNDP and other government and non-government institutions in the region. We would like to acknowledge all the support that made it possible for us to design and apply a realis- tic and flexible tool that enables users to calculate the energy costs embedded in efforts to achieve the MDGs. First and foremost, we would like to express our sincere thanks to Dr Hafiz Pasha, UNDP Assistant Administrator and Regional Bureau Director for Asia and the Pacific who encouraged and challenged us to prepare a costing tool that reflected the energy security issues threatening the achievement of MDGs in the Asia Pacific region.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "392edb2d-de63-4c34-ad02-ea212ba83292": {