gions they need to insert additional columns, and all the required linkages in all the relevant worksheets need to be created to get the final results. This requires a reasonably high level of expertise in using Excel and understanding the equations/formulas. TABlE 3: Prioritized subregions Sub regions Rural Rural 1 Rural 2 Rural 3 Rural 4 Urban Urban 1 Urban 2 Urban 3 The classification of sub regions under the two categories of 'Rural' and 'Urban' could be based on indicators related to demographics, economic development or geographic diversification Table 4 illustrates the Excel sheet for entering demographic and sectoral information. The data need- ed here is crucial for all future analyses. All forecasts made in the Tool depend on the accuracy of the information entered here. TABlE 4: Demographic and sector details Categories Units Rural 1 Rural 2 Rural 3 Rural 4 Urban 1 Urban 2 Urban 3 Population No. 476,147 90,695 Population growth rate for next 5 years % 2.5 3.8 Population growth rate for next 10 years % 2.4 3.8 Density No./km2 20 20 Family size No. 6.3 6.3 Health centres/hospitals No. 10 10 - Growth rate % 2 2 Educational institutions No. 100 100 - Growth rate % 3 3 Markets/community centres No. 100 100 - Growth rate % 2 2 Government institutions No. 15 15 - Growth rate % 1 1 Other institutions No. 25 25 - Growth rate % 1 1 Small and micro-industry No. 100 100 - Growth rate % 4 4 Agricultural pumpsets No. 1000 1000 - Growth rate % 3 3 Other agricultural uses No. 234 234 - Growth rate % 2 2 Rural transport No. 1500 1500 - Growth rate % 5 5 Demographics and sector details 4. Instructions for using the Energy Costing Tool 21 \u2022\ufffdThe data entry is self-explanatory (Table 4). The base year population needs to be entered for all the selected subregions in the first yellow-coloured row. \u2022\ufffdIn the next two rows, the estimated region-wide average population growth rates need to be entered for the next five years, as well as for the next 10 years (wi