 the estimated emission factors (in CO2 kg/unit quantity of energy). The list of energy carriers and electricity generation technologies is quite exhaustive and the need for adding any new alternatives is minimal. The options considered for electricity generation include both conventional fossil-fuel-based as well as renewable energy technologies. Additionally, the options include both large-scale centralized and small-scale distributed technologies. TABlE 5: Energy carriers and emission factors Category CO2 kg/unit 2.5 2.9 0 0 2.68 0 0 0.69 0.756 0.15 0.15 0 0 0.996 0 0.64 0.748 0.676 0 0 2.5 2.83 0 0 2.856 2.496 0 0 Small diesel power Petrol Kerosene Existing grid Sustainable biomass Heat energy for agro-processing, micro-industry and households (only rural) Agriculture and Transport (only rural) Ethanol Wind power Fuel oil Biogas power Solar home lighting Solar PV Diesel Sustainable biomass Kerosene Solar (Drier) Solar (Cooker) Solar (Water heater) Biomass gasifier power Energy carriers for end-uses and their emission factors LPG Modern fuels for cooking & heating Natural gas Electricity for lighting, mechanical power, other household, agriculture and micro- industry end-uses (rural and urban) Biogas Biodiesel Fuel oil Type Micro-hydro Grid diesel Grid hydro Grid natural gas Grid coal In the case of most of the energy carriers/electricity technologies, the emission factors used are stand- ard ones from the literature. However, average emission factors for the existing grid depend on the 22 Energy costing tool user\u2019s guide composition of the grid and need to be estimated by the user. In the case of some of the carriers, there may be some variations in the emission factors presented here. If the correct emission factors are avail- able those can be entered appropriately. Solar energy with zero CO2 emissions is recommended for thermal applications such as solar cookers, solar water heaters and solar driers. Emissions from sus- tainable biomass, biogas, micro-hydro, grid-hydro, biodiesel and ethanol have been assumed to be zero. If the users have a different perception they can enter the correct values. The part of the worksheet illustrated in Table 6 needs inputs in terms of energy carrier prices for all the chosen energy carriers. Only in the case of biofuel, is the price determined from analysis carried out in another worksheet. Average prices prevailing in the country could be used. In the case of biomass, the prevailing market price or that estimated in the \u2018Energy production\u2019 worksheet can be used (this esti- mate can be used only if the biomass is sourced from a sustainable energy plantation). TABlE 6: Energy carrier prices and electricity grid mix Fuel prices Fuel USD Kerosene (litres) 0.25 LPG (kg) 0.54 Retail diesel (litres) 0.80 Wholesale diesel (litres) 0.624 Petrol (litres) 1.25 Fuel oil (litres) 0.499 Coal (tonne) 34.60 Natural gas (M3) 0.070 Biomass (kg) 0.030 Dung/Leafy biomass (kg) 0 Solar (GJ) 0 Oil (KL) 85 Biodiesel (litres) 0.53 Ethanol (litres) 0.50 Type % Coal 0 Hydro 0 Small hydro 0 Natural gas 0 Diesel 100 Fuel oil 0 Wind power 0 Total 100 Average plant load factor (%) 45 Type USD Choice Average cost of supply (Overall) 0.06 0 Average cost of supply (Capital) 0.02 0 Average cost of supply (Recurring) 0.04 0 Marginal cost of supply (Overall) 0.22 1 Marginal cost of supply (Capital) 0.03 1 Marginal cost of supply (Recurring) 0.18 1 Existing electricity grid Mix (%) Existing Electricity Supply Cost/kWh Please enter '1' if you want to use 'Average cost of suppy' and '0' if you want to use 'Marginal cost of supply' for costing electricity from existing grid The second part of Table 6 shows how the information on the existing electricity grid mix (as in the base year) should be provided. The data required is in terms percentage share of installed capacity or pow- er generation (share in total generation) from different types of electricity generating technologies. 4.", "start_char_idx": null, "e