cts the actual current electricity generation cost. If the policy mak- er feels that the historical costs are more relevant than the future cost of generation (marginal", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a72bcad4-e7ae-45b0-9320-cbd4528b3612": {"__data__": {"id_": "a72bcad4-e7ae-45b0-9320-cbd4528b3612", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy Costing Tool: User Guide", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d069761d9657a308b66707cf62a84a5bc428d7cb13f9b49038150bd6dc58575c"}}, "hash": "d069761d9657a308b66707cf62a84a5bc428d7cb13f9b49038150bd6dc58575c", "text": "cost) then the average cost could be used. The average cost is estimated by averaging the cost of electric- ity generation from all the existing power generation plants. Two components of the average cost, the capital cost and the operating cost (or recurring cost) need to be obtained. \u2022\ufffdThe marginal costs (per kWh) are the cost of generating electricity from the new installed capacity of different types of primary energy (coal, natural gas, hydro, etc.). If the policy maker wishes to use the cost of generating the incremental unit of energy rather than the historical cost then he or she can use the marginal cost. The marginal cost for the existing grid is estimated by taking the weight- ed average of the unit costs of electricity generation from new installed capacity. The weights are determined by the shares of various capacities in the existing grid. In the cyan-coloured cell, the users need to enter \u20181\u2019 if they want to use the average cost of supply, or \u20180\u2019 for marginal cost of supply. The details of average cost of supply need to be entered by the user where- as the details of marginal cost of supply are obtained from the \u2018Electricity production\u2019 worksheet. The average cost of supply is the estimate arrived at by averaging the cost information obtained from all the existing power plants. The marginal cost of supply is the cost of adding the incremental unit of energy. 4.3 Costing energy production The \u2018Energy production\u2019 worksheet (Table 7) has been created for estimating the cost of producing energy carriers which are not traded in the market and for which market prices are not available. Biogas, sustainable biomass and biodiesel come under this category. The first few rows give infor- mation on units of measurement used for various parameters. For example, the unit of capacity for biogas is m3/day whereas it is hectare for sustainable biomass. Similarly, the unit of energy production is m3 for biogas and tonne for biomass. The last rose-coloured row contains information on the type of input fuel required to produce the necessary energy carrier. The part of the worksheet coloured yellow (Table 7) indicates that the user needs to provide the data required for analysis. As mentioned earlier, the Energy Costing Tool has been designed and developed in such a way that the first column provides row-specific descriptions for all the subsequent columns. From the second column onwards, calculations are performed for each of the chosen technologies to estimate the unit cost of energy production based on the input data (entered in yellow-coloured cells). For a given technology (say biogas), the assessment begins with defining units of measurement and ends with various cost estimates per unit of energy (per m3 for biogas). One column of a worksheet is adequate for assessing one technology. For repeating such an assessment for the next chosen tech- nology, just copy the column of data to the next empty column. Make appropriate changes, such as the name of the energy production technology, units of measurement and type of fuel inputs. Enter the relevant data in the yellow cells of the new column. With these changes, the required results for the new technology will be automatically obtained. 24 Energy costing tool user\u2019s guide For example, in the illustrated case (Table 7), if the data entry and calculation procedures are estab- lished for biogas, then replicating this for sustainable biomass and biodiesel is very easy and just requires copying the biogas columns into new empty columns and making the necessary changes as suggested above. The cells in the next two rows (coloured tan) contain data obtained from the linked cells of the \u2018Design parameters\u2019 worksheet. The cells in yellow-coloured rows are crucial for the user of the Tool. The data specific to each technol- ogy needs to be obtained and entered here. Some of the data is standard, which need not be changed and some other data is country-specific. The user has to obtain such country-specific data to make costing valid for a particular country. To support data entry, the following points would be useful: \u2022\ufffdlife (years): Enter the typical life span of the energy production facility. The data needs to be changed only if the user feels that the numbers entered here are inappropriate and they have the correct ones. \u2022\ufffdConstruction time (years): Enter the construction time required to build the production facility. The data needs to be changed only if the user feels that the numbers entered here are inappropri- ate and they have the correct ones. \u2022\ufffdNumber of crop rotations: This is relevant only for sustainable biomass", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c838d361-de56-44f3-a80f-1f5aed4be4fe": {"__data__": {"id_": "c838d361-de56-44f3-a80f-1f5aed4be4fe", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy Costing Tool: User Guide", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6db93aa9a49ee738a5dfecf9433188060889cff093bcceaf44513aafc2feda4a"}, "3": {"node_id": "ea6afa52-856b-4fa6-94e2-f28d56c600c3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5e35f26cb79392d7ebb5fb9e9a53991a72b315d957719af8c1086602911ddd35"}}, "hash": "3ee4e48f802e778826ed9279c98dfbcd14f9e9e7b429bce3eb2ecf7000c711b8", "text": "production. Here the assumption is that the energy plantation is of fast growing eucalyptus. It has been estimated that one hectare of eucalyptus gives 64 tonnes of fuel wood three times in 24 years (a total of 192 tonnes in 24 years). That is a rotation period of 8 years with 3 rotations in 24 years. The user can provide new data for an alternative fast growing species if available. \u2022\ufffdCapacity: The user should enter the capacity of the energy production plant. The capacity is given in terms of energy production per unit of any physical measure. In the illustrated case, the biogas plant considered is small scale, with a biogas production capacity of 8 m3 per day. The capacity consid- ered for a sustainable biomass production plant is one hectare and that for a biodiesel plant is 3000 tonnes per year. The user can make appropriate changes to the capacities of the plant with suitable changes to other parameters. \u2022\ufffdProduction per rotation per unit: This is relevant only for sustainable biomass production and the required explanation is given above. \u2022\ufffdCapacity factor (%): This is determined by the number of hours in a year the energy production plant functions. If it functions throughout the year without fail, then a number of 100% is entered. Otherwise appropriate percentages must be calculated. \u2022\ufffdCost of capital equipment in input currency: The user needs to enter the total capital cost (or investment) required to establish the energy production facility. This is country- specific data. All the monetary data needs to be entered in a single input currency (preferably the national currency). \u2022\ufffdCapital cost of distribution system in input currency: This is relevant only for biogas plants. This is the total capital cost required to establish the distribution system to supply biogas to individual houses. This is country-specific and needs to be revised. \u2022\ufffdAnnual o&M cost per unit of capacity in input currency: This is the annual cost incurred for oper- ation and maintenance (O&M) of the production facility. This cost needs to be given per unit of capacity (as explained above). \u2022\ufffdFuel requirement per unit of capacity: This is an input fuel consumption norm. This data needs to be changed only if new information is available. In the illustrated case, this data is relevant only for biogas and biodiesel. 4. Instructions for using the Energy Costing Tool 25 \u2022\ufffdPrice paid for fuel per unit in input currency: In the situation illustrated in Table 7, the input fuel for biogas (dung) is assumed to be free since equivalent amount of fertilizer can be returned to the supplier of the dung. However, this assumption can be changed and an appropriate price can be entered. In the case of biodiesel, the input fuel is crude vegetable oil (or raw oil) and the price per unit of raw oil needs to be entered. \u2022\ufffdhuman resource requirement (No.): This is the number of workers needed to operate the energy production facility. \u2022\ufffdWorking hours per day: This is the number of working hours needed to operate the facility per day. The workers need not work full-time to operate these plants and wages will be paid accordingly. \u2022\ufffdAverage wage rate in input currency per day (of 8 hours): This is the average wage rate prevail- ing in the country. TABlE 7: Estimating unit cost of energy production All the costs are in (Unless mentioned) USD Descriptions Biogas Sustainable biomass Biodiesel Units of capacity M3/day Hectare tonne/year Units of energy production M3 tonne KL Units of energy GJ GJ GJ Units of fuel requirement kg tonne Fuel Dung Veg.Crude Oil, Methanol, Potassium hydroxide Discount rate (%) 10 10 10 GJ/Unit of energy 0.023 15 23.4 Life (Year) 25 24 25 Construction time (Years) 0.5 0.5 No. of crop rotations 3 Capacity 8 1 3,000 Production per rotation per unit 64 Capacity factor (%) 100 Cost of capital equipment in input currency 740 122 400,000 Capital cost of distribution system in input currency 550 Annual O&M cost per unit of capacity in input currency 20 150 107,000 Fuel requirement per unit of capacity 26.5 0 3,000 Price paid for the fuel per unit in input currency 0 0 481 Human resource requirement (No.)", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ea6afa52-856b-4fa6-94e2-f28d56c600c3": {"__data__": {"id_": "ea6afa52-856b-4fa6-94e2-f28d56c600c3