opriate for the country", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d0aab13e-1feb-487c-8d54-656f3f8245a1": {"__data__": {"id_": "d0aab13e-1feb-487c-8d54-656f3f8245a1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy Costing Tool: User Guide", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "184938468fdd628027e9a4de81b81c15d8ff5728eb186ee5020070ef77a18b1e"}}, "hash": "184938468fdd628027e9a4de81b81c15d8ff5728eb186ee5020070ef77a18b1e", "text": "does it need to be corrected. \u2022\ufffdCost of capital equipment in input currency: The user needs to enter the total capital cost (or investment) required to establish the energy production facility. This is country-specific data. All the monetary data needs to be entered in single input currency (preferably the national currency). \u2022\ufffdEngine cost in input currency: This cost is relevant only for small-scale power generation plants which use diesel engines (small diesel power, biogas power and biomass gasifier power). This is the total capital cost of engines given the size of the power generation facility. This is country-specific data and needs to be revised by the user. The engine cost is required separately because the life of an engine is significantly shorter than that of the power plant as a whole. Therefore there is a need for frequent overhauling and replacement of engines during the life of the project. \u2022\ufffdoverhauling frequency (hours): Overhauling is an engineering process to recondition a diesel engine for continued use. A diesel engine needs to be overhauled every 6,000 hours to extend its life. Only three such overhaulings are possible for an engine, after which it needs to be replaced. The data of 6,000 hours only needs to be changed if the user has authentic alternative information. \u2022\ufffdoverhauling cost in input currency: Here the user needs to enter the cost of overhauling, applica- ble in the country. \u2022\ufffdNumber of overhaulings possible per engine: As explained above, this is three per engine. \u2022\ufffdAnnual o&M cost per unit of capacity in input currency: This is the annual cost incurred for oper- ation and maintenance of the power generation facility. This cost needs to be given per unit of capacity (as explained above). \u2022\ufffdPrimary fuel requirement per unit of electricity (per kWh): This is basically an input fuel (primary or main fuel) consumption norm. This data only needs to be changed if new information is available. 28 Energy costing tool user\u2019s guide \u2022\ufffdSecondary fuel requirement per unit of electricity (per kWh): This norm is similar to the prima- ry fuel norm. This is relevant only for small-scale distributed power plants like biogas power and biomass gasifier power, which use diesel engines as part of the generation plant. Here the second- ary fuel is diesel. Even in the case of grid-based coal thermal power plants, a small quantity of oil is required as secondary fuel. This data only needs to be changed if new information is available. \u2022\ufffdhuman resource requirement (No.): This is the number of workers needed to operate the energy production facility. \u2022\ufffdWorking hours per day: This is the number of working hours needed to operate the facility per day. The workers need not work full-time to operate these plants and wages will be paid accordingly. \u2022\ufffdAverage wage rate in input currency per day (of 8 hours): This is the average wage rate prevail- ing in the country. The average wage rates are high in the case of small-scale distributed power generation technologies because the human resource required is of a mix of unskilled, skilled and technical capabilities. The above explanations are also valid for Table 10. Table 9 illustrates the analytical section of the \u2018Electricity production\u2019 worksheet. A series of steps are performed to arrive at the unit costs. The unit costs are estimated per unit of electricity (kWh) and per unit of energy (GJ). The table also contains the estimates of human resource cost per unit of electricity for different technologies. As explained previously, having completed the analysis for one technology, replicating the analysis for the subsequent technologies is a simple process; just copy the completed column and paste it into the next empty column. Only the data in the yellow cells needs to be changed to get the new unit cost estimates for an electricity generation technology. This way one can devel- op the worksheet for all the required technologies. However, in the illustrated case, such a worksheet has already been built containing all currently available technologies. Only country-specific data need be revised. The cells in the last few rows provide results of the analysis. (Please refer to Annex 2 for a detailed explanation of the procedure adopted for unit cost estimation.) The above explanations are also valid for the worksheet illustrated in Table 11. 4. Instructions for using the Energy Costing Tool 29 TABlE 9: Analysis performed for estimating unit cost of electricity Life of the plant (Years) 25 25 25 25 25 25 25 25 Construction time (Years) 0.5 0.5 0.5 0.5 3 4 3 4 Capacity of the plant 20 20 20 2 100 500 250 500 Working hours/year", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_templa