ces, the first few rows are related to units of measurement and the linked data from the earlier sheets. The data required for this analysis is limited to the following: \u2022\ufffdCapital cost of the end-use device in input currency: The capital or purchase cost of the end-use device (e.g. kerosene stove) needs to be entered here. In the case of lighting it may be difficult to provide the capital cost of end-use devices because there is large variety of lighting devices being used, in terms of cost, power input, technology and light output. With this in mind, it is advisable to use the total cost of all the lighting devices in a typical household. This would be the average capi- tal cost of lighting devices in a household. \u2022\ufffdlife of the device (years): The life of the end-use device needs to be entered here. For lighting, an average needs to be estimated and entered. \u2022\ufffdAnnual maintenance cost in input currency: Some of the end-use devices may require some cost to be incurred annually for maintenance. If information on such costs is available then that needs to be entered here. \u2022\ufffdoverall efficiency of the device (%): Again, if the relevant information is available then please enter the efficiency of the end-use device. For lighting, it has to be the overall average efficiency. It is relatively easy to obtain the above details for energy end-use devices used in households. Howev- er, such information would be difficult to obtain for end-uses in other sectors/institutions (represented in Table 13). Even in the case of households, if we want to capture the cost of utilization of electrici- ty for other end-uses (other than electricity) it is difficult to get the above information because of the large variety of devices. Again, we need to rely on average cost, overall efficiency, etc. This is also true for other institutions, such as community organizations, micro-industries, etc. In the case of electricity, the end-use cost estimates presented here also include the cost of provid- ing final connection at the premises. This is obtained from the \u2018Electricity production\u2019 worksheet as a linked cell.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "056181d6-d902-4ff9-8d37-150c7a631aac": {"__data__": {"id_": "056181d6-d902-4ff9-8d37-150c7a631aac", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy Costing Tool: User Guide", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "143e75b79d00da841430e4797ba7c3cbc56d48e8bc9607da3dcbeb536765fc4f"}, "2": {"node_id": "91c85529-76f5-4332-ac2e-907dcf43d2a3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5b90611f77e1858ef2d4059faec29648144b785d06e20b2439b8f29dceaf673f"}}, "hash": "7e0dd5a84d3b01e63c110a865a96d7f2a465a32e329973272d101a995b633d64", "text": "This is obtained from the \u2018Electricity production\u2019 worksheet as a linked cell. (Please refer to Annex 3 for a detailed explanation of the procedure adopted for unit cost estimation.) 4. Instructions for using the Energy Costing Tool 33 All the costs are in (Unless mentioned) USD Solar (Drier) Biogas Kerosene LPG Sustainable biomass Natural gas Solar (Co