c00fd96e329b46ff66450a8b5df0d04b70a559", "text": "Instructions for using the Energy Costing Tool 35 4.6 MDG needs targets Tables 14 to 18 show the various parts of the worksheet that have been developed for entering the MDG needs targets for increasing access to modern energy carriers and end-services. The targets are those arrived at through a consultative process and are the outcome of decisions made by policy makers. The targets are fixed in terms of percentage, keeping the base year achievements as a refer- ence, and are based on the resource potential (capital and energy) and energy needs for achieving the MDGs. Targets need to be estimated for each of the end-use sectors, energy carriers and energy technologies. In the illustrated case, the targets are estimated for two terminal years, short-term (for 2010) and long-term (for 2015). These depend on the planning target years provided by the user in the \u2018Design parameters\u2019 worksheet. Thus, the MDG energy needs assessment is carried out for three sce- narios: Baseline (2006), 2010 and 2015. Compared to other worksheets, the \u2018MDG needs\u2019 worksheet is quite complex in terms of usage of colour codes. Here all possible colour codes are used; for data entry, decisions, decision support infor- mation, linked cells, etc. New colour codes, which are not present in other worksheets, are cyan and blue. Cyan indicates that the user needs to enter the information (as targets) based on the outcome of a decision-making process. Blue indicates that the information available could be used for arriving at some of these decisions. Table 14 represents the part of the work sheet that has been developed for entering targets for access to modern fuels for cooking and to modern cooking systems (or devices) in the household. The first part of Table 14 deals with overall access to modern cooking fuels across regions whereas the second part deals with fuel access. This division has been made to simplify the data entry process. The details of data entry requirements are as follows: \u2022\ufffdAll the information on fuel names, subregions, etc. is obtained from other worksheets and the users should not alter this. \u2022\ufffdBaseline (2006): Access levels to modern fuels are derived from fuel access levels. The cells are linked and therefore coloured tan. \u2022\ufffdTarget", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8089be73-a2bf-4f9d-a084-e9a69e65ef25": {"__data__": {"id_": "8089be73-a2bf-4f9d-a084-e9a69e65ef25", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy Costing Tool: User Guide", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2423f4351c6974b59ee042b3a85a01085edae10b1cc2801b1dbf5a4e6061e65f"}}, "hash": "2423f4351c6974b59ee042b3a85a01085edae10b1cc2801b1dbf5a4e6061e65f", "text": "for 2010: Based on baseline access levels, the target access levels (as percentages) need to be determined and entered for all the chosen subregions. These targets are the outcome of a deci- sion-making process and are therefore coloured cyan. \u2022\ufffdTarget for 2015: This is similar to the above process but needs to be based on targets set for 2010. \u2022\ufffdBaseline access levels for modern fuels: The user needs to obtain data (or estimates) on current access levels (as percentages) for all modern fuel types across all selected subregions. The cells are coloured yellow, indicating that they are data entry cells. \u2022\ufffdFuel access targets for 2010: To simplify the data entry, as well as the decision-making processes, the fuel access targets need to be entered only for two main regions (rural and urban). The subre- gion targets are calculated using these regional targets and the overall targets determined above. The user needs to determine targets for all the modern fuels specific to rural and urban regions and enter this in cells coloured cyan. The information on cost/unit of useful output in GJ (in blue-col- oured cells) can be used while fixing targets and arriving at prioritization of fuel types. For example, the targets could be high for cheaper alternatives. \u2022\ufffdFuel access targets for 2015: The procedure here is similar to that used for fixing targets for 2010. It is important to keep in mind that the fuels are replaceable and fuel shifts are possible. 36 Energy costing tool user\u2019s guide TABlE 14: MDG access targets for modern cooking fuels and improved cooking systems Term years Rural 1 Rural 2 Rural 3 Rural 4 Urban 1 Urban 2 Urban 3 2006 10 0 0 0 80 0 0 2010 20 0 0 0 90 0 0 2015 50 0 0 0 100 0 0 2006 Fuels Cost/unit of useful output in GJ Rural 1 Rural 2 Rural 3 Rural 4 Urban 1 Urban 2 Urban 3 Kerosene 11.98 10 0 0 0 20 0 0 LPG 18.95 0 0 0 0 60 0 0 Sustainable biomass 6.01 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 Biogas 8.85 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 Natural gas 4.94 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 Solar (Cooker) 2.42 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 Solar (Water heater) 39.15 0 0 0 0 5 0 0 Total 10 0 0 0 80 0 0 2010 Fuels Cost/unit of useful output in GJ Rural Urban Rural 1 Rural 2 Rural 3 Rural 4 Urban 1 Urban 2 Urban 3 Kerosene 11.98 75 30 15 0 0 0 27 0 0 LPG 18.95 10 70 2 0 0 0 63 0 0 Sustainable biomass 6.01 10 0 2 0 0 0 0 0 0 Biogas 8.85 5 0 1 0 0 0 0 0 0 Natural gas 4.94 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 Solar (Cooker) 2.42 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 Solar (Water heater) 39.15 0 7 0 0 0 0 6.3 0 0 Total 100 100 20 0 0 0 90 0 0 2015 Fuels Cost/unit of useful output in GJ