80\u2019 for all coverage targets associated with the intervention. This will eliminate the interven- tion from resource estimates. 4.9.2 Changing interventions To change to a different kind of intervention, users should go to the \u2018Design parameters\u2019 worksheet and change the name of the intervention. If the calculation steps for the intervention remain the same as the one it is replacing, then changing the names of the cells in the \u2018Design parameters\u2019 worksheet should be sufficient.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7f4fe416-eee5-4060-b0ad-f8b0fc73765c": {"__data__": {"id_": "7f4fe416-eee5-4060-b0ad-f8b0fc73765c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy Costing Tool: User Guide", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "cc0257531684f2c4a162ad124b05a3011a360c41ee28f7ca66d63fd1c015bc1c"}, "2": {"node_id": "06d7f2c7-0fb0-450e-89d2-1a20f4466d91", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "95ceb708ea20b69bd50041f1e14418ace1b04ff8922dee6fbd6b6eaa0ad4c494"}}, "hash": "159732495ea51ec756c76bcd71615143794f4177d7c4d8433cb52133793db141", "text": "Otherwise, the user will need to ensure that appropriate fields (or cells) and for- mulas are entered for the new intervention. 4.9.3 Adding interventions Additions in terms of new energy supply technology, end-use or subsector are possible in the Tool and advanced users should find it relatively easy to add columns or rows and link them throughout to the relevant worksheets. The process needs to be carried out in the correct sequence. The first addi- tion has to happen in the \u2018Design parameters\u2019 worksheet. The next change, depending on the type of intervention, should happen in the \u2018Energy production\u2019, \u2018Electricity production\u2019 or \u2018Energy end-use\u2019 worksheets. In these worksheets, adding an intervention is", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "730c6ee9-910b-49a0-a399-ad1a9e0be455": {"__data__": {"id_": "730c6ee9-910b-49a0-a399-ad1a9e0be455", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy Costing Tool: User Guide", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5e485aebdc0469ac011a90fd3184a2b320fac072b694efdefc187665bf59294e"}, "3": {"node_id": "ecea1f8d-887f-41d8-8ba2-8a0bb51dea90", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "aef80dd6cf803485103e232c819500388d1386dbb513f5c9cbe451aeaf711788"}}, "hash": "f175d5d2d84ee157e821efe8b879aca2f4c897cbd839f4bb8fa13dc305abee43", "text": "achieved by copying the previous column of information into the next empty column and inputting the new data in the yellow-coloured cells. In the next step, appropriate additions depend on the interventions in the \u2018MDG needs\u2019 worksheet. Next, the new interventions have to be replicated in the scenario worksheets. Finally, the summary page should be updated to include these changes. 4.10 Checking results and trouble-shooting Once results have been derived from the Energy Costing Tool, how can the user tell whether the results are realistic? One way is to check the totals obtained by using the Tool against results for other countries by com- paring the per capita costs. The UN Millennium Project\u2019s \u2018Preparing National Strategies to Achieve the Millennium Development Goals: A Handbook\u2019 provides some illustrative per capita figures (in dollars) for investment needs, including for energy, which can be used for comparisons. 52 Energy costing tool user\u2019s guide Other ways to check results include examining the path of per capita expenditures over a 10-year peri- od and running internal checks on cost drivers: Path of per capita expenditures: One way to check for major errors is to study the 10-year path of per capita expenditures. If there are any unusual spikes or troughs, or other patterns, users may need to re- examine scale-up paths and other formulas in calculations. Internal checks on cost drivers: Another way to assess results is to analyze the major drivers of total resource needs. Cross-country comparisons suggest that costs for improved fuels will contribute 40 to 50 percent of total cost estimates. Primarily because of this, cooking systems typically make up 50 to 60 percent of total costs. If there are large variances in one or more of these costs, the user may wish to re-examine some of the unit costs, the outcome/coverage targets, or input quantity ratios and com- pare them to international standards to identify the source of variance. 4.10.1 Trouble-shooting During the course of the costing exercise, users may also encounter a number of modeling issues and problems. Here, we discuss some of the most common problems and identify simple tools that may help resolve them. 1) Unrealistically high or low resource estimates After comparing results with comparable estimates, the user may find that the model has produced unrealistically high or low values. A bit of detective work will be in order, moving from general to spe- cific issues. \u2022\ufffdAre any of the cost drivers significantly higher or lower than cross-country benchmarks? \u2022\ufffdAre there any large spikes or troughs in the pattern of resource needs? (This might indicate a typo- graphical error in a single year\u2019s entry.) \u2022\ufffdAre all of the coverage and input quantity ratio targets accurate? \u2022\ufffdAre the unit costs reasonable? \u2022\ufffdAre recurrent and capital costs calculated correctly? (If the calculations are mixed up, or based incor- rectly on incremental vs. cumulative figures, results may be unrealistically high or low.) \u2022\ufffdAre results highly sensitive to small changes in variables? If so, users should be very careful in inter- preting results. 2) #VALUE If the symbol \u2018#VALUE\u2019 appears in a cell, the problem is most likely that the user has entered an inap- propriate value for the variable (e.g. text in a cell that accepts only numbers). If inappropriate values are entered into cells that are used to calculate values in other cells, all the dependent cells will also display the #VALUE symbol. If confronted with this problem, the user should click on a cell where the #VALUE symbol is displayed and go to the \u2018Tools\u2019 menu, select \u2018Auditing\u2019, and click on \u2018Trace precedents\u2019. By following the arrows backwards to the cell with the original error, the user should be able to iden- tify and correct the problem. 4. Instructions for using the Energy Costing Tool 53 3) #REF If the symbol \u2018#REF\u2019 appears, a link has been broken, most likely by deleting a precedent cell. If the #REF symbol has just appeared, go to the \u2018Edit\u2019 menu and select \u2018Undo\u2019, which may bring back the deleted cell and solve the problem. If this does not help, select a cell where the #REF symbol appears and try to assess what cell might have been deleted or moved. Many #REF problems can be avoided by following two simple rules.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ecea1f8d-887f-41d8-8ba2-8a0bb51dea90": {"__data__": {"id_": "ecea1f8d-887f-41d8-8ba2-8a0bb51dea90", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy Costing Tool: User Guide", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5e485aebdc0469ac011a90fd3184a2b320fac072b694efdefc187665bf59294e"}, "2": {"node_id": "730c6ee9-910b-49a0-a399-ad1a9e0be455", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f175d5d2d84ee157e821efe8b879aca2f4c897cbd839f4bb8fa13dc305abee43"}}, "hash": "aef80dd6cf803485103e232c819500388d1386dbb513f5c9cbe451aeaf711788", "text": "Many #REF problems can be avoided by following two simple rules. First, before deleting any cell, select it and use the \u2018Auditing\u2019 function (under the \u2018Tools\u2019 menu) to \u2018Trace dependents\u2019. If there are any dependents, make sure that their formulas are appropriately modified before deleting the cell. Second, when moving cells or rows from place to place, always \u2018cut\u2019 (from the \u2018Edit\u2019 menu) and then \u2018paste\u2019 (also from the \u2018Edit\u2019", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "81322fae-f487-4eee-9974-0d90d03eb299": {"__data__": {"id_": "81322fae-f487-4eee-9974-0d90d03eb299", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy Costing Tool: User Guide", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8597c373360499f2ae19e390e4777ee7aeaff50566b17efbc4c11d27bfd1bb48"}, "3": {"node_id": "cdbf5e94-f952-416c-9629-f27716e97d90", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "62954855b7f77144ae6e7651bf85e82df34cfec8144b606666a49f4df5ccb47a"}}, "hash": "a3a5720ec3b16999b5fd16913e8561b11c61a4fb9b77eee4032921ad2b6588d8", "text": "menu). Never perform \u2018copy\u2019 and \u2018paste\u2019. Cutting and pasting updates all the links; copying and pasting does not. 4) #DIV/0! The \u2018#DIV/0!\u2019 symbol means that a formula involves division where the denominator is zero, yielding an undefined result. When this occurs, examine the formula and check the precedent cells to ensure that the values are correct. More often than not, the #DIV/0! symbol appears when an entry has been accidentally deleted and used as the denominator in a quotient formula, yielding this readily resolva- ble problem. 4.11 Conclusion and next steps This Guide has been prepared to introduce and facilitate use of the Energy Costing Tool as part of a strategic planning and budgeting process that will bring countries closer to achieving the MDGs. Those Goals were adopted in 2000, with a target date of 2015, so there is an urgent need for action. By making the proper types of long-term investments now, governments and institutions can make it possible to meet the Goals, and bring much-needed relief to the many people around the world cur- rently suffering from hunger, lack of education and health care, and social inequities. At the 2005 World Summit, world leaders reiterated their support for the MDGs by committing to the development and implementation of MDG-based national development strategies, and acknowl- edged that energy is a fundamental element of such actions. This acknowledgement was founded on the understanding that without increased access to modern energy services for the poor, the MDGs are unlikely to be met. Realistic costing information can provide a bridge that will move policy and planning wish lists past the financial constraints that stand in the way of coordinated development initiatives \u2013 by providing a framework for combined pro-poor investments from a variety of sources, including businesses, com- munities, civil society groups and international donors, as well as national governments. The Energy Costing Tool is in the in process of being tested, and is presented as a useful tool for inte- grating energy investments into medium- and long-term fiscal planning. It is hoped that the Tool will prove to be an effective vehicle for helping governments and planners move towards the incorpora- tion of MDG-based budgeting. As it is more widely applied, we expect that additional adaptations and improvements will be developed, and the Tool will be modified and updated in response to further testing and feedback from users. 54 Energy costing tool user\u2019s guide References 1. Columbia University and United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) Energy Workshop, Energy Services to Meet the MDGs: Cost Estimates for Senegal, May 2006. 2. Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) and West African Economic and Monetary Union (UEMOA), White Paper for a Regional Policy: Geared towards increasing access to energy services for rural and peri-urban populations in order to achieve the Millennium Development Goals, January 2006. 3. Energizing the Millennium Development Goals: A Guide to Energy's Role in Reducing Poverty Publisher: UNDP/BDP Energy and Environment Group 4. Energizing Poverty Reduction: A Review of the Energy-Poverty Nexus in Poverty Reduction Strategy Papers: Minoru Takada; Ndika Akong Charles \u2013 lead authors, 2006\u201311 5. UN Millennium Project, Preparing National Strategies to Achieve the Millennium Development Goals: A Handbook, October 2005. 6. UNDP and Energy For Sustainable Development 7. United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), Integrated Package of Services to Support MDG-Based National Development Strategies, December 2005. 8. United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), Making Sense of MDG Costing, August 2004. 9. World Bank/Energy Sector Management Assistance Program (ESMAP), United Nations Development Pro- gramme (UNDP) and UN Millennium Project, Energy Services for the Millennium Development Goals, 2005. Annexes 55 Annexes ThESE ANNExES IllUSTRATE the calculation steps that are included in the Energy Costing Tool. Since the calculation steps and the formulas used are repeated for different types of technologies, end-uses and subsectors, it was felt that it would suffice to give explanations for the step-by-step procedure adopted for one each of these three types. Secondly, these descriptions have been limit- ed to only the relatively complicated calculation procedures because most of the other calculations involve either addition or multiplication operations and they are self-explanatory. Descriptions are given alongside the formulas as they appear in the Excel worksheet.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "cdbf5e94-f952-416c-9629-f27716e97d90": {"__data__": {"id_": "cdbf5e94-f952-416c-9629-f27716e97d90", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Energy Costing Tool: User Guide", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8597c373360499f2ae19e390e4777ee7aeaff50566b17efbc4c11d27bfd1bb48"}, "2": {"node_id": "81322fae-f487-4eee-9974-0d90d03eb299", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/energy-costing-tool-user-guide", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Devel